<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Blocks Arts Endowment Increase
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans used an eleventh-hour maneuver Thursday to
block what almost became the first significant budget increase for the National
Endowment for the Arts that the House has approved since 1992. Arts advocates
had moved to the edge of a surprise victory for the endowment with a preliminary
207-204 vote. Their goal was to add $15 million to the $98 million a fiscal 2001
spending bill contains for the agency, long in the crosshairs of GOP
budget-cutters and at the center of a partisan culture war. But Republican
leaders headed off the move by crafting an amendment that diverted the
additional money to Indian health services. That amendment prevailed by voice
vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Says Plan Would Ensure Coverage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans said Thursday their plan for
prescription drug insurance for the elderly envisions federal financial
incentives to insurance companies to make sure coverage is available nationwide.
''We've tried to allow as much flexibility with this ... to accommodate any
scenario that we might be able to run into,'' said Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C.,
among the architects of the GOP plan. A new draft summary of Republican
legislation being prepared for House action -- possibly as soon as next week --
offered no details about how much such incentive payments might cost.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Sees Two Cities in One
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton took a tale-of-two-cities tour of
Washington on Thursday and found signs of hope in each. In one of the poorest
neighborhoods, where barbed wire stands guard around empty lots, Clinton
celebrated the growth of an after-school learning center called the U.S. Dream
Academy where children, some with parents in prison, use the Internet to connect
with knowledge. ''What you do for these children, someone should do for every
child in the United States,'' Clinton told parents, administrators and some
excited but restless youngsters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Feds Make Big Heroin Bust
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agents made more than 170 arrests Thursday as they
broke up a multimillion-dollar Mexican heroin ring alleged to have smuggled
unusually pure and cheap black tar heroin into new markets from one U.S. coast
to the other. The gang, based in the Nayarit state of Mexico, was distributing
80 pounds of heroin each month, worth more than $7 million, in 22 U.S. cities,
said Joe Keefe, chief of special operations for the Drug Enforcement
Administration. The ring was marketing the heroin at such a high level of purity
and such a low price that the Mexicans pushed into eastern U.S. markets formerly
served by Colombian drug traffickers, Keefe said in an interview.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Names New Head of Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Al Gore named Commerce Secretary William Daley to take
over his presidential campaign Thursday in the second major shake-up of his
political operation, replacing Tony Coelho who abruptly resigned citing health
problems. Daley, son of former Chicago Mayor Richard Daley and brother of the
city's current mayor, is known as a savvy political operator with ties to both
President Clinton and Gore. Daley is a household name in Illinois, an important
presidential battleground.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wildfires Raging in Colorado
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DRAKE, Colo. (AP) -- Blowtorch winds gusting to 60 mph whipped up two
wildfires and sent flames racing Thursday, forcing firefighters to retreat and
driving hundreds more people from their homes in the foothills outside Denver.
More than 200 National Guardsmen were called in to join the 1,500 firefighters
already battling the two blazes. The fires have burned nearly 15,000 acres and
destroyed about 50 structures, mostly homes, since Monday. Before the flareup
today, about 800 people had been evacuated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tighter Pollution Rules Considered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Southern California will decide Friday whether nearly
11,000 transit buses and garbage trucks must convert to cleaner-burning
alternative fuels -- a move that could lead to similar requirements across the
country. Under the plan, believed to be the first of its kind in the nation,
every new vehicle purchased by public fleet operators will have to run on
alternative fuels -- natural gas, methanol, electricity or fuel cells.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher Friday, boosted by gains in U.S.
stocks. The Nikkei rose 75.06 points to 16,413.76. On Wall Street Thursday, Dow
Jones industrial average rose 26.87 to close at 10,714.82. The Nasdaq finished
up 48.33 at 3,845.74.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pirates Defeat Braves 2-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kris Benson pitched a six-hitter for his first career
shutout and drove in the first run with an infield single, leading the
Pittsburgh Pirates past the Atlanta Braves 2-0 Thursday night. Benson (5-5),
outdueled Kevin Millwood (4-6), holding the middle of the Braves' order to one
hit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
