<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acid Leak Reported in Derailment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLTON, Calif. (AP) -- A freight train derailed Thursday in a
rail yard, spilling diesel fuel and shutting down two offramps of
busy Interstate 10. fire officials said. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen cars went off the tracks at 3:18 p.m. a few miles west
of San Bernardino. The cause of the derailment was not immediately
determined, county fire spokesman Dave Dowling said.
</P>
<P>
   A tanker car held sulfuric acid but it did not spill.
</P>
<P>
   A locomotive usually carries 2,000 gallons of diesel fuel,
county Fire Marshal Peter Brierty said. Colton Fire Department
spokeswoman Kathie Saidon said less than 50 gallons spilled.
</P>
<P>
   The I-10 exits were shut down as a precaution, but traffic
continued to flow on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Brierty said the immediate hazard was a CalNeva liquid fuel
pipeline 4 feet below ground. CalNeva workers were checking whether
there was a rupture, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0020 </TRAILER>
