<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daley steps into Gore Arena  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though Bill Daley is a prominent member of one
of the country's most famous Democratic families, his favorite
quote comes from a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   On the table in his vast Commerce Department office is a framed
quotation from President Theodore Roosevelt. The Rough Rider says
that credit in life goes not to the critic but to ''the man who is
actually in the arena; whose face is marred by dust and sweat and
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley was summoned Thursday by Al Gore to enter the biggest
political arena of all, taking over the job as chairman of the vice
president's campaign against Republican rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the legendary Richard J. Daley, mayor of Chicago for
two decades, and brother to the current mayor, Richard M. Daley,
Gore's new campaign chairman is no stranger to political arenas.
</P>
<P>
   And Daley, 51 years old with a distinctive bald dome, is also
familiar with uphill political fights.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation in the Clinton administration is as the rescuer
of lost causes. He came in and pushed for congressional passage of
the North American Free Trade Agreement with Mexico in 1993 and
then again this year he helped win House passage of a landmark
trade agreement with China.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of the NAFTA victory, Clinton presented Daley
with an autographed photo of the two of them in the Oval Office,
with an inscription thanking him for his help on the ''Lazarus
Project.'' Like the biblical Lazarus, NAFTA had been given up for
dead before Daley arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned to Daley again this year to head up the
administration's all-out effort to win passage of legislation that
would end Congress' annual review of China's trade privileges with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To both battles, Daley brought his political instincts, learned
in the rough and tumble of Chicago politics, first in growing up in
the mayor's household and then as one of his older brother's most
trusted advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Daley was actually Gore's first choice for campaign chairman
last year, but he was not ready to leave the Cabinet, a Gore aide
said, and so Tony Coelho got the job. Coelho resigned, citing
health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Coelho frequently consulted Daley, who was helping
with convention planning. Daley chaired the 1996 convention in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration, Daley at first was passed over
for a Cabinet job, accepting the consolation prize as head of the
NAFTA war room. His performance put him at the head of the list to
fill a Cabinet post after Clinton won re-election.
</P>
<P>
   His introduction to the media as Clinton's Commerce nominee in
December 1996 proved disastrous. Daley, who hadn't taken time to
eat that day, fainted on the stage as Clinton was speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's handling of the scandal-plagued Cabinet department has
proven much more sure-footed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress had accused Clinton's first Commerce
secretary, Ron Brown, of stocking the agency with political
operatives and using trade missions as payoffs for big Democratic
campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   In response to those attacks, Daley instituted a number of
reforms, putting in place a revamped selection process for trade
trips and eliminating a hundred political jobs at Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's selection as campaign chairman won praise from
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''This guy is probably the best person in America to be in
charge of this campaign,'' said Al From, head of the centrist
Democratic Leadership Council, citing his experience in Washington
and the heartland.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping in Illinois, a battleground state, Daley
is expected to provide strong links to the business community.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley's role in the bruising battle over NAFTA and China,
both of which were strongly opposed by organized labor, could cause
problems with that key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters spokesman Bret Caldwell called Daley's appointment ''a
big slap in the face to organized labor.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO and an ardent Gore
supporter, said Daley's stewardship of NAFTA and the China trade
bill ''put him squarely on the opposite side of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Wilhelm, a former chairman of the Democratic National
Committee and head of Clinton's 1992 campaign, said he didn't
believe labor's unhappiness would end up hurting Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Daley certainly had good working relations with organized
labor in Chicago,'' said Wilhelm, who also managed the campaign of
Daley's brother. ''I think the people in organized labor will find
that his door is open.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley said he will move to Nashville to take over the campaign.
That won't prove disruptive to his family life because Daley's wife
and three children stayed behind in Chicago after he joined the
Clinton Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has explained that it was easier that way because when he
wasn't out traveling the country and the world on Commerce
business, he was usually spending his time at the office anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
