<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian Women Question Future  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA BRYSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syrian women stride the streets of their
capital in sleeveless T-shirts, even the occasional miniskirt,
while many of their sisters elsewhere in the Arab world wrap
themselves in veils and cloaks. It's a small sign that Syria
harbors modern ideas about what its female citizens can do and be.
</P>
<P>
   But Syrian women say it's far from true equality and many wonder
whether a Western-educated leader -- 34-year-old Bashar Assad,
anointed this week as his father's successor -- will help improve
their lot.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad, who died Saturday after three decades in power, was
credited with doing much to advance the cause of women's rights.
But tradition and culture didn't change overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Assad peppered his speeches with calls for women's
emancipation. His Baath Party was one of the first Arab parties to
make women's equality a platform plank, declaring in its 1946
constitution that ''the Arab woman enjoys all the rights of
citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Syrian women attend Damascus University in large numbers -- an
estimated 90 percent of its medical school students are women,
though the percentage of women teachers lags. Working women are
concentrated in teaching or medicine; few run their own businesses.
One runs a state bank; two sit on the Cabinet, as ministers of
culture and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they complain of limited opportunities and of struggling
to be treated as equals in the workplace -- then returning home to
husbands who expect them to end their day at the office with an
evening of housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ''All Syrian men want women at home. All men -- even educated
men, even if their wives are educated,'' said Dr. Gemma Adib, an
anesthesiologist who was one of 30 women in a class of 180 to
graduate from Damascus University in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women Adib went to school with stopped working when
they married. Adib, who is unmarried, pooled her resources with
three other women and opened a cosmetics factory six years ago -- a
business she runs in addition to her medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from medical school in Damascus and completing
specialized courses in Washington, D.C., Dr. Leila al Droubi sold
her apartment and took out a loan to open her own business 11 years
ago, a health club where Syrians could exercise under medical
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Al Droubi's family, though supportive, feared it was too much of
a challenge for a divorced mother. Her friends advised playing it
safe and working at a hospital. But she persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tiled-and-mirrored complex employs 24 people and is
crowded with treadmills, weight machines and brightly colored
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, a room where al Droubi now holds private
exercise classes was her son's nursery. Few of her friends worked,
and she remembers crises of confidence -- worries that she was
spending too much time on business and not enough on her son, Omar.
</P>
<P>
   On one particularly frustrating day, Omar, then just 7 or 8,
comforted her. ''He said, 'Mom, do you think the other mothers who
don't work spend all day talking to their kids? They're on the
phone or watching videos ... I'm proud of you,''' she recounted.
''He made my day.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think society made me pay any price for my choice.
People accepted me. Not only accepted, but respected me as a
successful woman. Women who don't think they will be accepted for
not conforming, they're just afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Many women, though, did not have the opportunities of the
44-year-old al Droubi. Her late father, a Baath party leader and
former ambassador, encouraged her independence. By taking his
family on his overseas posting, he also ensured she was exposed to
new ideas and possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the traditional assumption that girls should be raised
only to be wives and mothers remains, and some accuse the Baath
Party of trying to change Syria too fast.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and 1980s, Assad's younger brother Rifaat -- now a
dissident but at the time his brother's top lieutenant -- recruited
women as well as men to serve their country, with the daring
romantic dream of parachute training.
</P>
<P>
   His ''girl parachutists'' became the bane of Islamic
fundamentalists, even storming the streets of the capital, ripping
veils from more conservative women. During a 1982 fundamentalist
uprising in the central city of Hama -- swiftly and brutally put
down by the government -- two young women parachutists were killed
in their beds by Islamic rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Maysa H. Diab, an art historian who runs her own antique shop,
says she has to work twice as hard to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ''People think that men are more committed, more prepared,'' she
said. But Diab, 43, is hopeful her 21-year-old daughter will find
more opportunities when she returns home from a university in Texas
to look for a job in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just wait one more generation,'' she said. ''The girls who are
in their 20s now are learning from their mothers' mistakes. Their
mothers are sitting at home doing nothing and very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic and enterprising of Syrian women,
though, say real change may be slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Bashar is going to make some changes. Maybe not
immediately -- that would create chaos,'' said Diab.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the late president's progressive pronouncements, Assad
made a traditional choice when it came to grooming an heir,
selecting Bashar over his first-born, a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Diab rejected any suggestion Hafez Assad could have prepared his
daughter Bushra, said to be his favorite child, to take over Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, no,'' Diab said. ''Men are more accepted in this
society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0105 </TRAILER>
