<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Hurts Middle East Economies  </HEADLINE>
By IBRAHIM BARZAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   EREZ CROSSING, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Ali Sultan's permit to enter
Israel expired 20 days ago and his two trucks, which normally ferry
cargo between the Israeli port of Ashdod and the Gaza Strip, have
been standing idle.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan and tens of thousands of other Palestinians have been
locked out of Israel by a six-week-old strike of a few hundred
Israeli civil servants who issue entry permits at the crossings
from the Palestinian areas into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Palestinian Authority retaliated by blocking
Israeli goods from the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The border showdown has hurt both economies and illustrated how
much Israel and the Palestinians need each other, despite their
political conflict -- and likely will continue to do so even if the
Palestinians win independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli and Palestinian economies became linked when Israel
captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip during the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   During the Israeli military occupation since, the Palestinian
areas were a source of cheap labor for Israel and an outlet for
Israeli products. At the same time, Israel restricted investment in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   After the establishment of Palestinian self-rule in 1994, the
lopsided relationship continued, often exacerbated by Israeli
security closures that kept Palestinian laborers from jobs in
Israel for prolonged periods.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Palestinians have won some degree of economic
independence, said Samir Huleileh, a Palestinian economic analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The value of imports from countries other than Israel grew from
$54 million in 1994 to $800 million. The number of Palestinians
licensed to work in Israel has decreased from 120,000 in 1994 to
45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ties remain strong. Exports to the Palestinian areas make up 15
percent of Israel's trade, while the Palestinians send 80 percent
of their products to Israel, said Shlomo Dror, spokesman for the
Israeli liaison office with the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial parks with both Israeli and Palestinian factories
have been established in border areas. Israelis and Palestinians
have set up joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
   However, the balance is easily upset.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, several hundred employees of the Israeli military
government in the West Bank and Gaza, the so-called Civil
Administration, launched a strike for better employment conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The strike meant that Palestinians whose permits expired could
not renew them. For now, only 27,000 laborers and 3,000 merchants
still have valid entry passes to Israel, but most will expire by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of others have been locked out, although some
from the West Bank have been able to slip through a porous border.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military officials have tried to stand in for the Civil
Administration workers, but the effort was cut short when the
stand-ins ran out of the special paper used for the permits and
could not obtain a new shipment, Dror said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the strike, close to $100 million worth of goods
intended for Gaza are stuck in Ashdod port, said Nasser Saraj,
director general of the Palestinian Trade Ministry. Palestinian
officials have said the Palestinian economy is losing several
million dollars a day in lost wages and income.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Palestinians began turning Israeli trucks away
from Gaza, and on Wednesday, the Palestinian Trade Ministry ordered
them kept out of West Bank cities as well. An exception was made
for a truckload of cows from Israel that suffered badly in the
stifling heat and were allowed into Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Dror said the Israeli government has gone to a labor court to
obtain a back-to-work order, and complained that the blockade was
counterproductive. But the Palestinians said this was the only way
to prod Israel to end the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan, the Palestinian trucker and father of nine, said he has
been losing about $1,000 a day. ''This is a destruction of the
Palestinian economy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0113 </TRAILER>
