<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Ponder Mexico Election  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- During Mexico's last presidential election
six years ago, guerrillas had seized much of southern Chiapas
state, the ruling-party candidate had been assassinated and a
Catholic cardinal had been killed in the cross fire between drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe President Ernesto Zedillo was elected by a ''vote
of fear,'' at a time when unrest was so great that people were
afraid to cast their ballot for anything other than the party that
has now governed Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the July 2 election has been prefaced by relative
calm. But as opposition candidate Vicente Fox surges in the polls,
some analysts say the possibility remains that old-school ruling
party members could try to encourage violence -- or at least fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mexican political culture accepts the use of violence as a
political instrument,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a historian at the
Colegio de Mexico research institution.
</P>
<P>
   The elements of unrest are already in place:
</P>
<P>
   --Two guerrilla groups -- the Zapatista National Liberation Army
in Chiapas and the Popular Revolutionary Army, based in Guerrero
state -- continue to operate. Five other splinter groups of the
Popular Revolutionary Army are recruiting and occasionally carrying
out attacks.
</P>
<P>
   --Drug-smuggling gangs have stepped up their violence in recent
months, leaving bodies in streets and ranches along the U.S.
border. Although no national figures are available, analysts say
it's clear there's been an upsurge in killings this year.
</P>
<P>
   --A conflict with students of Mexico's prestigious National
Autonomous University in Mexico City continues months after police
raided the campus and arrested many of the leaders of a nearly
10-month strike. Negotiations remain stalled.
</P>
<P>
   --Social groups from across the country have stepped up their
protests in Mexico City, clogging traffic and occasionally clashing
with police. The protests concern low salaries and diminishing
funds for public education.
</P>
<P>
   Aurelio de la Vega left the guerrillas in the eastern mountains
of Mexico 20 years ago to become a deacon at a Roman Catholic
church. He says there's no reason to think there won't be violence
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The seedlings of the guerrilla movements are planted, and the
need, misery and corruption that caused them hasn't changed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say with only weeks to go before the election,
violence and unrest can have only a minimal effect on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there will be a vote of fear because it's too
late to create it, and I don't think any movement can have the
spectacular impact of the Zapatistas,'' said Sergio Aguayo, an
academic who studies national security.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ''The risk of instability in Mexico is always
latent because violence has always been a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   One way in which this year's election is different from previous
ones is that, unlike other Mexican leaders, Zedillo has gone out of
his way to ensure a fair vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zedillo won't back any fraud,'' said Jorge Chabat, a
researcher on drug smuggling and national security.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a president who got there almost by accident, and if the
ruling party loses, he won't worry too much. He's more worried
about entering history as the president who allowed the democratic
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if violence doesn't spark a vote of fear, there are
indications that the ruling party is trying to use memories of
unrest to scare people into voting for its candidate -- and for a
perceived stability.
</P>
<P>
   Election monitoring groups report that local ruling-party
candidates have told people they would lose welfare benefits if the
ruling party lost the election, or that the country would spiral
into crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
