<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Blocks Arts Endowment Increase  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans used an eleventh-hour maneuver
Thursday to block what almost became the first significant budget
increase for the National Endowment for the Arts that the House has
approved since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Arts advocates had moved to the edge of a surprise victory for
the endowment with a preliminary 207-204 vote. Their goal was to
add $15 million to the $98 million a fiscal 2001 spending bill
contains for the agency, long in the crosshairs of GOP
budget-cutters and at the center of a partisan culture war.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders headed off the move by crafting an
amendment that diverted the additional money to Indian health
services. That amendment prevailed by voice vote, with most
lawmakers unwilling to deny money for health programs serving some
of the poorest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the move ignited bitter attacks by Democrats, who
accused Republicans of cynically using Indians to deny money to the
arts agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''You use them as cannon fodder in your crusade against the
arts,'' said Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., adding, ''This isn't
about priorities. This is about a political trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., who sponsored the GOP
amendment, said his amendment was aimed not at blocking money for
the arts but at helping Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't do it all,'' he said, citing budget constraints. ''I
hate to have you prescribe bad motives to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., asked ''are we to believe''
Nethercutt, ''the same man who supported term limits and now is
reversing himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt is among several House Republicans first elected in
1994 who promised to serve only three two-year terms. He is running
for re-election this year anyway, citing a desire to serve his
district.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying spending bill provides $2.4 billion for Indian
health services, $30 million more than this year but $200 million
less than President Clinton wants. The overall bill, which finances
land and cultural programs, was approved by 204-172.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know we have a majority of bipartisan support in the
House,'' endowment spokeswoman Cherie Simon said after the vote.
''But because our opponents once again would not allow a fair
fight, we now look to the Senate to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the spending bill has not yet been
written, but that chamber usually provides more money for the arts
agency than the House does.
</P>
<P>
   The arts endowment began in 1966 with a $2.9 million budget that
grew to $176 million by 1992. But under conservative fire for
endowment grants that financed controversial art exhibits, its
funds began to slowly shrink.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans took over Congress in 1995, they sliced its
budget to $99 million for the 1996 fiscal year and proposed
abolishing the agency by 1998. But amid defections from moderate
Republicans, the agency survived -- though its budget had drifted
down to $97.6 million by this year.
</P>
<P>
   In its 207-204 vote Thursday, the House approved an amendment by
Rep. Louise Slaughter, R-N.Y., to take $22 million out of a clean
coal technology program. Twenty-five moderate Republicans defected
to support Slaughter's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan was to give $15 million to the arts agency, $5 million
to the National Endowment for the Humanities and $2 million for
museums and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has requested $150 million for the arts endowment for
fiscal 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0115 </TRAILER>
