<DOCNO> APW20000616.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Mulls Congo Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council is hoping a two-day
meeting of the warring factions in Congo's 2-year-old civil war
will boost the prospects for peace and cement the withdrawal of
Rwandan and Ugandan forces from the northern city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   The council is negotiating a French-sponsored draft resolution
that would demand the two former allies withdraw immediately from
the city, where they exchanged intense fire earlier this month,
killing an estimated 300 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But the draft also calls on Rwanda and Uganda and the three
other foreign armies fighting in Congo to withdraw from the country
as a whole, as called for by a peace agreement signed last year in
Lusaka, Zambia -- and threatens possible sanctions if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how the council would make that demand -- and whether
Rwanda and Uganda would be called on to leave the country by a
specific date. Presumably that would be before the departure of
Namibia, Angola and Zimbabwe, which are in Congo at the invitation
of the government to help fend off rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
   France, which is president of the Security Council this month
and is hosting the Congo meetings, hopes to adopt the resolution by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda entered Congo's war 22 months ago as allies
supporting rebels who wanted to topple President Laurent Kabila.
They say they are in Congo to protect their borders from their own
rebels operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, they battled each other in Kisangani, even
after agreeing to U.N. cease-fires and to withdraw from the
strategic city. The fighting ended Sunday after Rwandan forces
drove the Ugandans out of the northern sector of Kisangani and let
unarmed U.N. military observers deploy between the two former
allies.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at the start of a two-day meeting of the half-dozen
warring countries and Congo's main rebel groups, the U.N. special
representative for Congo asked the council to authorize about 250
armed U.N. soldiers to move into Kisangani quickly to maintain the
peace after Rwandan and Ugandan troops leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kamel Morjane said the deployment was specific for Kisangani to
fill a vacuum that had been created by the unusual situation of two
allies turning their guns on one another.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any vacuum could be very dangerous, especially for the future
of the whole process -- not only for Kisangani,'' Morjane told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. resolutions call for a 5,537-strong force made up of 500
observers and four battalions of armed security forces to protect
them to deploy around the country. So far, just 228 members of the
force have been deployed in Congo and in liaison offices in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Morjane said that because of the difficulty in rounding up troop
contributions, he was seeking 240 soldiers to be sent to Kisangani
quickly. But, he said, that number would not be able to keep
security in the city and about 700 soldiers would be required.
</P>
<P>
   Council diplomats noted that a significant troop increase for
Kisangani had been envisaged previously but said the draft
resolution being negotiated on the sidelines of the two-day Congo
meetings wouldn't contain any new mandate requirements for the U.N.
force.
</P>
<P>
   That would have to come later, they said, without giving any
timeframe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000616.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Chinatown Deals With Change  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The face of Chinatown is changing in cities
all over the country, shaped mostly by tireless urban revival and
development.
</P>
<P>
   This city's century-old neighborhood has joined the ranks. With
a new baseball park in the works for the Philadelphia Phillies, the
community is facing a change many say will be too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's the death knell of Chinatown,'' said Mary Yee,
who lives in Northeast Philadelphia but has frequented the shops
and restaurants of Chinatown since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark would be built on the northern edge of Chinatown, a
mix of residential, industrial and small business properties. The
City Council must still approve the stadium and a price tag
expected to be nearly twice that of building a stadium outside the
city center.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the ballpark would eliminate Chinatown's last
remaining frontier for development. Chinatown leaders also say the
quality of life in the already overcrowded area would be ruined by
45,000 baseball fans trooping through 80 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''People will move out and businesses will find some other
neighborhood to invest in,'' Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinatowns nationwide are historically vulnerable to change
because they are a landing ground for new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The tightly packed, inner-city neighborhoods offer dirt-cheap
apartments and entry-level jobs. Residents usually move out of
their cramped quarters as soon as they acquire job and language
skills.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Chinatown still has about 14,000 residents, but
only about half of them are Asian and just one-third are
non-citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not that Chinatown is dying, but the face of it is
changing and many things are being lost from a cultural and ethnic
basis,'' said Arnold Chin, co-chairman of San Francisco's Chinatown
Economic Development Group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now people go to new Chinatowns, the mini-Chinatowns around
the San Francisco area. These have Chinese grocery stores and the
mom-and-pop stores that cannot afford rents downtown anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, people are leaving the crime-riddled downtown
Chinatown to settle in suburban Monterey Park's Chinese community.
Boston's Chinatown, located at the mouth of an expressway tunnel,
is also the red-light district. In Washington, D.C., Chinatown was
swallowed by the new MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Overall, all Chinatowns are not doing well,'' said Peter
Kwong, an Asian-American studies professor at Hunter College in New
York. ''Usually the least powerful political group is the Chinese.
That leads to urban development projects dumped in Chinatown.''
</P>
<P>
   Only New York's Chinatown, North America's largest with more
than 70,000 residents, continues to thrive and grow mostly due to
the city's inexhaustible need for unskilled laborers in factories,
warehouses and thousands of restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, 70 percent of Chinatown's 4,000 residents speak
no English, but the area also serves an estimated 250,000 Chinese
in the region, according to the Philadelphia Chinatown Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood was mostly young male immigrants running a
handful of restaurants and one grocery store until the mid-1960s,
when immigration laws changed allowing thousands of Chinese and
Asian families to move to America. Women and children congregated
at the Holy Redeemer School and Church, the only school in the area
and a meeting site for the new Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, the city proposed an eight-lane highway that
would bulldoze Holy Redeemer and cut Chinatown in half. The school
was spared, though the expressway was built through the community.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we saw it as a plan to get rid of Chinatown,'' said
Cecelia Yep, who has lived in Chinatown since the mid-1960s. ''It
was the only thing good in Chinatown at the time. We thought it was
a fight for survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar plans came up many times over the next 30 years, with a
federal prison, commuter rail tunnel, downtown mall and convention
center. Each was built with much compromising, and now they form a
circle around Chinatown's current core of about five city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chinatown is a symbolic center not just for the people who
live there, but for the Chinese-American community as a whole,''
said Debbie Wei of Philadelphia. ''What happens to Chinatown
becomes a symbol for what happens to us as a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Wei grew up in the Philadelphia suburbs, but her family came to
Chinatown every weekend for church and shopping. She now lives a
few blocks from Chinatown with her own kids and said she fears the
cultural costs of building a stadium in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ethnic enclaves have always been the backbone of urban
development in America,'' she said. ''Each of these communities
contribute to the lifeblood of the city. When one of them is wiped
out and made extinct, it is an unalterable loss to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
