<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands Fighters Share Food  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Fighters from the Solomon
Islands' warring factions put down their weapons and shared food
and hugs Friday at a frontline checkpoint, a sign that the latest
flare-up in a simmering ethnic dispute was easing.
</P>
<P>
   But after a friendly meeting of about an hour, the fighters took
up their guns again and vowed not to disarm until a peace deal has
been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting erupted last week on the main island of Guadalcanal
over a land rights dispute between the island's indigenous Isatabus
and people from the neighboring island of Malaita. For the past 18
months, the Isatabus have been forcing thousands of Malaitans off
land they have been settling on in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that the government failed to protect them, the Malaitans
raided an armory, seized the capital and demanded the resignation
of democratically elected Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu, who
quit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before stepping down, Ulufa'alu organized a special 12-member
committee made up of an even mix of government and opposition
leaders who will try to negotiate a peace deal with the rival
islanders. Ulufa'alu, who is serving as a caretaker prime minister,
said the goal was to resolve the tensions within two weeks so that
parliament, without acting under duress, could pick a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   In a spontaneous gesture, fighters from both sides came out of
their bunkers and met Friday on a bridge at Alligator Creek, on the
outskirts of the capital Honiara.
</P>
<P>
   ''After seeing them wave to us, we left our arms and walked
toward their bunker,'' said Amos Anilafa, a Malaitan rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''They sent militants to meet us ... we hugged each other and
shook hands. Some of us shed tears. We felt love for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed that peace must be immediately restored (and) that
the government must give us amnesty to create a pathway to lasting
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came amid new appeals Friday for an end to tensions
that have caused the collapse of the government and is threatening
to destroy the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated that men haven't brought peace, a group of about 70
women wearing scarfs of yellow, blue and green -- the colors of the
national flag -- approached the warring groups with a simple
message: Stop fighting and talk peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think as mothers, they are our sons. We brought them here
in our wombs and we love them and we want them to lay down their
guns,'' said Margaret Aihunu, a teacher who joined the women at a
rally in Honiara before leaving to meet the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the special committee, Governor General John Ini
Lapli, urged the rebels to seek a peaceful end to their disputes
and help repair the nation's democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''You all are endowed with wisdom and intelligence,'' Lapli said
in a national radio address, ''and you must use it to improve
yourselves, your communities and your beloved country, the Solomon
Islands.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Malaita rebels said they would allow police to
take over the security of the capital. But they have not returned
weapons that they took from the police and it was unclear how the
police could patrol unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of the conflict have been honoring a 14-day
cease-fire, which expires next week.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the Isatabus are content with controlling the
countryside and the Malaitans lack the will and resources to expand
their territory beyond the capital.
</P>
<P>
   With many of the homes and shops empty in the capital, the main
source of revenue -- the retail industry -- has suffered and many
large factories have had to shut down because they can't find
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Islands lie 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney,
Australia. They were the scene of battles between the United States
and Japan during World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
