<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wind Sends Colo. Fire Toward Houses
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DRAKE, Colo. (AP) -- Blowtorch winds gusting to 60 mph whipped two wildfires
and sent flames racing Thursday, forcing firefighters to retreat and driving
hundreds more people from their homes in the foothills outside Denver. More than
200 National Guardsmen were called in to join the 1,500 firefighters already
battling the two blazes. But crews expected that calmer winds Friday would allow
firefighters to attack from the air again. The fires have burned nearly 17,200
acres and destroyed about 50 structures, mostly homes, since Monday. Before the
flareup Thursday, about 800 people had been evacuated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Feds Make Big Heroin Bust
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agents made more than 170 arrests Thursday as they
broke up a multimillion-dollar Mexican heroin ring alleged to have smuggled
unusually pure and cheap black tar heroin into new markets from one U.S. coast
to the other. The gang, based in the Nayarit state of Mexico, was distributing
80 pounds of heroin each month, worth more than $7 million, in 22 U.S. cities.
The ring was marketing the heroin at such a high level of purity and such a low
price that the Mexicans pushed into eastern U.S. markets formerly served by
Colombian drug traffickers, Keefe said in an interview.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
6 More Arrested in NYC Park Attacks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Six more men were arrested Thursday in the attacks on women
who were stripped and groped in Central Park last weekend. Investigators also
said they now believe the attacks may have involved as many as 60 men.
Previously, they had put the number at about 40. The number of possible victims
has risen from 24 to 32 as more women have come forward. The arrests Thursday
brought the total number of men arrested in the attacks to eight. Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said the men will probably be charged with sexual
assault.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Blocks Arts Endowment Increase
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans used an eleventh-hour maneuver Thursday to
block what almost became the first significant budget increase for the National
Endowment for the Arts that the House has approved since 1992. Arts advocates
had moved to the edge of a surprise victory for the endowment with a preliminary
207-204 vote. Their goal was to add $15 million to the $98 million a fiscal 2001
spending bill contains for the agency, long in the crosshairs of GOP
budget-cutters and at the center of a partisan culture war. But Republican
leaders headed off the move by crafting an amendment that diverted the
additional money to Indian health services. That amendment prevailed by voice
vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Small Privately-Held ISPs Endangered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Small Internet service providers that offer only
dial-up access are fighting for survival as telecommunication giants offering
high-speed access and free Internet providers squeeze them from both sides of
the market. The rapid expansion ofWorldCom Inc. and AT&AMP;T Corp. over the last
five years has ignited a feeding frenzy on large and mid-size Internet companies
and turned small ISPs into acquisition bait for the surviving regional dial-up
access providers looking for growth. If that isn't bad enough, at the other end
of the food chain, ISPs that offer free access to the Web are signing away
customers looking for a cheaper way to surf.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Says Plan Would Ensure Coverage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans said Thursday their plan for
prescription drug insurance for the elderly envisions federal financial
incentives to insurance companies to make sure coverage is available nationwide.
''We've tried to allow as much flexibility with this ... to accommodate any
scenario that we might be able to run into,'' said Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C.,
among the architects of the GOP plan. A new draft summary of Republican
legislation being prepared for House action -- possibly as soon as next week --
offered no details about how much such incentive payments might cost.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Urges Improved Vaccinations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vaccinations of America's toddlers may be at a record
high, but the immunization system is under critical strain and the country risks
disease outbreaks if it isn't strengthened, a new report says. Some 11,000
babies are born each day who need shots, thousands of unvaccinated inner-city
children remain at risk of epidemics -- plus there are millions of unimmunized
adults, the Institute of Medicine warned Thursday. The institute called on
federal and state governments to invest $1.5 billion over the next five years to
improve inoculations, about $175 million more per year than is now spent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher Friday, boosted by gains in U.S.
stocks. The Nikkei rose 75.06 points to 16,413.76. On Wall Street Thursday, Dow
Jones industrial average rose 26.87 to close at 10,714.82. The Nasdaq finished
up 48.33 at 3,845.74.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dodgers Beat Diamondbacks 4-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kevin Brown pitched a four-hitter for his third straight
complete game, and the Los Angeles Dodgers scored quickly in Todd Stottlemyre's
return to beat the Arizona Diamondbacks 4-0 Thursday night. Brown (6-2) got his
16th career shutout, his first since last Sept. 4 at Chicago. He struck out 10
and walked none, lowering his ERA to 2.18, second in the NL behind Arizona's
Randy Johnson (1.40). Stottlemyre (8-4), activated from the disabled list before
the game, was down 3-0 after six pitches, giving up home runs to Todd
Hollandsworth and Gary Sheffield around Mark Grudzielanek's double.
</P>
