<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bishops Discuss Priest Shortage  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD N. OSTLING
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The most pressing practical problem facing the
Roman Catholic Church is a growing shortage of priests that could
lead to fewer Masses, more priestless parishes and deacons leading
worship services, the nation's Catholic bishops say.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year study on the burgeoning problem was presented
Thursday to the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, which is
meeting in Milwaukee through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, there were 58,132 priests serving 46.6 million
parishioners in the United States. Today there are 20 percent fewer
priests and nearly a third more parishioners, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are the things will get worse over the coming
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark, N.J., said his diocese
projects the number of priests to drop from 540 to 192 in 20 years.
And Auxiliary Bishop Thomas Curry reported that due to immigration,
some parishes in the Los Angeles archdiocese have 18,000 Catholic
households.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problems are simply enormous,'' Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishops provided a range of explanations for the shortfall:
fewer parents encouraging church vocations, church negativism,
secularism and materialism in society, and a reluctance to make
permanent commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, the situation is bound to worsen due to
the rising average age of priests -- currently 57 for those working
in dioceses -- retirements and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   As for future recruits, 3,474 candidates are studying in
graduate-level seminaries, a 57 percent drop from 1965. A quarter
of the seminarians are foreign born. Additionally, major
archdioceses are ordaining fewer than 10 new priests this year.
</P>
<P>
   The only functions limited to priests are celebration of Mass
and granting absolution from sins. But in practice, Catholics
expect priests to preside at baptisms, marriages and funerals and
to participate in other parish functions.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Stephen Blaire of Stockton, Calif., summarized the
findings of 18 focus groups with priests around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many say they feel inadequate, stressed and exhausted,'' he
said. He quoted one priest as saying, ''There are just too many
expectations, too much paperwork and not enough ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Priests also expressed concern about ''increased isolation'' and
less mentoring from fellow priests.
</P>
<P>
   Two liberal groups, Call to Action of Chicago and the
Cleveland-based FutureChurch, issued a statement repeating their
call for married priests and women priests. Pope John Paul has
ruled out consideration of those changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're delighted that the U.S. bishops are finally beginning to
talk about the critical shortage of priests, but the solutions they
are proposing won't solve the problem,'' said the Rev. Lou
Trivison, co-founder of FutureChurch.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, bishops discussed a pending policy statement that
strongly criticizes the nation's criminal justice system and
indicated they are ready to endorse the measure to be voted on in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-page statement declares the criminal justice system ''is
not really working: victims are often ignored, offenders are often
not rehabilitated, and many communities have lost their sense of
security.'' It also repeats the U.S. church hierarchy's position
that capital punishment must be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there was ever a need for a statement, it is this one,''
said Bishop Joseph Fiorenza of Galveston and Houston, Texas,
president of the U.S. bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Cardinal Francis George said ''the freedom that should
characterize a free nation is reproached in the present system.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Conference site: http://www.nccbuscc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000616.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates Visit Figi Islands  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- An international delegation visiting Fiji to
press for the release of 31 political hostages welcomed the
military's commitment this week to restore a multiracial democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels who stormed parliament May 19 warned on Friday
that if the military plans to restore Fiji's 1997 constitution,
faltering negotiations to release the captives could collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the Commonwealth, an organization of
Britain and its former colonies, were meeting Friday with the
military as well as political, religious and indigenous groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the military understands only too well what the
consequences for Fiji are if Fiji does not return to a multiracial,
democratic and constitutional form of government,'' said
Australia's Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander Downer.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, the European Union and the United States have warned
that Fiji will be diplomatically and economically isolated unless
democracy is restored.
</P>
<P>
   Fijian nationalists, led by failed businessman George Speight
are holding 31 hostages including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry -- the first ethnic Indian prime minister -- in parliament.
They are demanding the country's ethnic Indian minority be stripped
of political power.
</P>
<P>
   The military, which declared martial law May 29, said Thursday
it wanted to see Fiji return to multiracial rule, while also
addressing the concerns of indigenous Fijians. Military spokesman
Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini said Fiji's 1997 constitution, which
the army had pledged to scrap, could form a basis for the country's
next constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they are saying that, they are treading on very dangerous
ground,'' said rebel spokesman Jo Nata. ''This whole thing began
because of distaste over the 1997 constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationalists say the constitution gave too much power to ethnic
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main disputes between indigenous Fijians and ethnic
Indians is over sugar, the nation's cash crop. Indian farmers built
the industry by operating plantations on land communally owned by
indigenous Fijians and leased at low rates set by English colonial
law. The leases are due to be renewed, and Chaudhry's refusal to
accept demands for higher rent enraged many Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Speight and his rebels were meeting Friday for a second day with
a delegation of Fijian tribal chiefs to discuss a resolution to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, when soldiers shot at Speight's car as it drove
through a roadblock, hundreds of supporters have trooped into
parliament. On Thursday, they brought food including home-baked
cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Civil unrest continues near parliament. A military spokesman
said soldiers fired warning shots Thursday night at a group of
people believed to have come from parliament who were looting a
nearby house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000616.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More arrests in attacks on women in Central Park  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Six more men were awaiting arraignment overnight
on charges they took part in attacks on at least 37 women in
Central Park following the Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   The six men were arrested Thursday, a day after police culled
their photos from amateur videotapes of the attacks and made the
pictures public.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference, Police Commissioner Howard Safir
said at least 50 calls were made to the NYPD's crime hotline about
other suspects, and he hoped more arrests would be made soon.
Photos of more suspects were released Thursday after victims
identified their alleged attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Eight men have been arrested in all, including two who were
taken into custody minutes after they allegedly attacked three
British tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said up to 60 men in various groups may
have participated in the attacks, in which girls and women were
doused with water, some groped and sexually abused, others robbed.
</P>
<P>
   One victim was only 14 years old, another a French tourist on
her honeymoon. All the attacks occurred in broad daylight, and the
majority of victims were assaulted in the southern end of the park,
near the Sixth Avenue entrance, the zoo, and across from the Plaza
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Safir identified two of the latest suspects as John Taylor, 24,
and Isaias Lozano, 19, both of Queens. He said he expected they
would be charged with sexual abuse, but the district attorney's
office will make the final determination.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, speaking on WCBS-AM news radio Thursday
evening, said he plans to propose legislation making gang sexual
assault a felony punishable by 3-5 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano was arrested at his girlfriend's house in Queens, Taylor
at his mother's home in the same borough. Manuel Nunez, 18, of the
Bronx, was arrested near his apartment there.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano, Taylor and Nunez were found after police received tips
called into the Crime Stoppers hotline. If the trio are indicted,
police will pay the tipsters $2,000 each; if convicted, the amount
rises to $10,000 apiece to each of the tipsters.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD detectives also went to Jersey City, N.J., to pick up
Steven Burt, 31, who surrendered to a parole officer. Burt wasn't
on parole at the time, but wanted to turn himself into a law
enforcement officer, said Assistant Chief William Taylor, head of
Manhattan detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ''He saw his picture in the paper and on TV, and he was
concerned that his friends were going to give him up,'' Chief
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said Burt had the right idea: ''I suggest that they (other
suspects) surrender also because we are going to find you and we
are going to find the others who are involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Vargas, 18, of the Bronx, described by police as a
suspected ringleader, surrendered himself to police late Thursday.
''He seems to have orchestrated a lot of what was going on, or at
least was a main player,'' Chief Taylor had said. Vargas was
identified by a tip to Crime Stoppers, and police had visited his
apartment but did not find him.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Camacho, 16, of Inwood, Long Island, also turned himself
in Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects arrested Sunday - David Rowe, 24, of Hempstead,
and Tremayne Bain, 23, of Brooklyn - were charged with
second-degree aggravated sexual abuse, first-degree sexual abuse
and second-degree robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe and Bain are friends, but police do not believe any of the
other men arrested had any connection to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised the police for the additional arrests, then
berated the media for focusing its coverage on allegations made by
several victims that police staffing the Puerto Rican Day parade
Sunday along neighboring Fifth Avenue did nothing to help them. The
mayor said the majority of officers did their jobs well that day.
</P>
<P>
   Both Safir and Giuliani again denied that police assigned to the
parade relaxed regulations on offenses such as drinking in public
due to tensions between the NYPD and minority communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
