<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State teachers to receive grants to work at local companies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Some of Connecticut's teachers will be
getting other jobs this summer, as part of an effort to better
prepare their students for the work force.
</P>
<P>
   In a program designed to give educators a better idea of how
their lessons are applied in businesses and industry, about 45 high
school teachers will be given summer jobs with Hartford-area
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers will bring their on-the-job experience back to the
classroom, designing curriculums based on their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Business and Industry Association is
administering $100,000 in grants to fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's students need a lot more information about what
careers are available,'' said Lauren Weisberg Kaufman, vice
president for education and training for CBIA. ''Many teachers have
only worked in an academic environment. They don't always have a
frame of reference if they haven't had the opportunity to see
firsthand what certain careers are all about.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, A science, geology and physics teacher will be
working at a housing construction site this summer. When She
teaches her physics class in the fall she will be able to say how
these concepts can be applied to heating, plumbing, carpentry and
electricity, Weisberg Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   Other teachers are slated to work in fields including arts and
media, business and finance, science, manufacturing, tourism and
construction technologies.
</P>
<P>
   After completing the program, the teachers will present
professional development seminars to other educators in their
school districts to help them get involved in school-to-career
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   CBIA is the state's largest business organization, with 10,000
member companies throughout Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
