<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescriptions Hot in Election Year  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Voters are intensely interested in making
prescription drugs more affordable for senior citizens. Most
politicians agree something needs to be done. And everybody from
presidential candidates to state lawmakers are scrambling aboard
the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds like a formula for getting results, even in an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Election pressures could increase the odds of Congress passing a
plan -- but President Clinton has said he wants Republicans to go
further in providing benefits than they have offered so far.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the political potency of the prescription drugs
issue, just listen to Nancy Ryman, a 72-year-old widow from Bay
City, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''My prescription drugs cost me $250 a month and I make $1,440 a
month from Social Security and my pension,'' said the retired nurse
with a heart ailment. ''I don't have any extra money. What do
people do who don't have as much money as me?''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people around the country -- including two of the most
consistent groups of voters -- feel strongly about the issue, polls
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Three-fourths of Americans age 61 and older say prescription
drugs will be very important in their presidential vote, according
to an ABC News poll last month. More significantly, two-thirds of
those between the ages of 45 and 64 -- people anticipating their own
medical needs in retirement and worrying about their parents -- rate
it as a very important issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the hottest issue we've seen in some time, in every
part of the country and every part of our membership,'' said John
Rother, legislative director for AARP, which lobbies on behalf of
older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is wrestling over what to do as Republicans rush to get
ahead of Clinton and Democratic congressional leaders on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a standard drug benefit under Medicare,
adding prescriptions to other health care services the program
covers if retirees pay an additional monthly premium. House
Republicans would enlist private insurers to sell
government-subsidized and approved prescription drug insurance
policies to Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday he had ''grave concerns about the GOP
proposal, which he said relied too heavily on private industry to
fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill Thomas, the California Republican and chief
architect of the GOP plan, said ''the private sector can do a great
job'' but that government would step in where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential contest, Democrat Al Gore favors providing a
standard Medicare drug benefit for those who choose it, while
Republican George W. Bush wants a bigger role for private industry.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats think it's a potent enough issue that it was the
subject of the Democratic National Committee's first TV campaign
commercial promoting Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When people were asked in the ABC poll who they trusted to do a
better job of handling prescription drugs, half said Gore and a
third said Bush. Women were more likely than men to say
prescription drugs were very important in their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Geoff Garin said the president and Democrats
feel public sentiment is strong enough to hold out for a big
solution, not a smaller-scale plan like the GOP offering.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers recognize the magnitude of the issue, too.
Almost half of states already have some kind of program to help
seniors pay for prescription drugs, said Richard Cauchi, a policy
specialist with the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Legislators report this is what their constituents are
clamoring for,'' he said. ''They see ways that states can afford to
do at least a piece of this. But a number of legislators hope
Congress will do something ... no state can afford to do a
Medicare-like benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican state Rep. Nancy Argenziano of Florida heard a clear
message while visiting constituents around the state to talk about
health care.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talk to constituents from different districts, the elderly
especially, and their number one cry to me was to help us with
prescription drugs. That was from the middle-income as well as the
poor,'' she said. Florida passed legislation this year providing
subsidies for some residents. And Texas Gov. Bush ''understands we
have to do something about the pharmaceuticals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired nurse Ryman is pessimistic a national agreement will be
reached anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just argue for arguments' sake,'' she said of the
politicians, adding that the people's concerns get left out.
''Republicans aren't going to do it to suit the Democrats and vice
versa.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Will Lester covers polling and politics for The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0228 </TRAILER>
