<DOCNO> APW20000616.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush May Have Hope in Massachusetts  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Massachusetts is home to such famous Democrats as
the Kennedys, but its Republican governor and lieutenant governor
give George W. Bush a glimmer of hope this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving Thursday for two fund-raisers aimed at generating more
than $1 million for the Republican National Committee, Bush joked
that he would only take the outcome of his home state of Texas for
granted in the fall matchup with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It was optimistic talk, considering Bush lost the Massachusetts
GOP primary in March to Sen. John McCain, 65 percent to 32 percent.
In 1988, the state's governor, Michael S. Dukakis, was the
Democratic presidential nominee against Bush's father, former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''I recognize it's a Democratic state, but there have been some
notable exceptions,'' said Bush, flanked by Gov. Paul Cellucci and
Lt. Gov. Jane Swift. ''The only state that's almost certain is
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was heading to Canton, Ohio, on Friday for a visit to
Passages School, an alternative school for at-risk students.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor is fond of blasting ''the soft bigotry of low
expectations,'' saying all children can learn if placed in the
appropriate setting.
</P>
<P>
   Passages School, part of the city school district, is an
alternative place of learning for pupils who have been expelled or
suspended from their local public school.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal is to provide a personalized education program,
allowing them to return to their regular schools. Students are also
encouraged to perform community service.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier in South Portland, Maine, Bush outlined a
five-year, $880 million plan to remove ''the last barriers to full,
independent, productive lives'' for the disabled on the job and at
home.
</P>
<P>
   And he kicked off a series of GOP fund-raising events netting
nearly $5 million in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also commented on the loss of computer files containing
nuclear weapons secrets from a New Mexico lab, saying the matter
was ''of great concern.'' He blamed the Clinton administration for
''another major security lapse'' and said he supports an
investigation into the missing files.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like all Americans, I'm deeply concerned about security lapses
at Los Alamos and I look forward to finding out what the facts
are,'' Bush said. ''I think it's very important that security be
tight. This is an administration that promised no more security
lapses and then there was another major security lapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he already had spoken with former Tennessee
Sen. Howard Baker, who is leading the investigation with former
Indiana Rep. Lee Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that, if elected, he would not be deterred in his
efforts to build a national missile defense system. Defense
Secretary William Cohen faced opposition this week from Russian
President Vladimir Putin during discussions about a limited missile
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll find out how good of a diplomat I am,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On the money front, he attended a $100,000 fund-raiser in Maine,
followed by two events in Boston raising $1 million. After school
Friday in Ohio, there is a $500,000 Republican National Committee
luncheon followed by a $600,000 event in Kentucky on behalf of the
state party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was closing the week with events Saturday in Florida
expected to raise $2.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Thursday, the Republican National Committee
announced a new ad targeted to Hispanic voters. The 30-second spot,
to begin airing Monday in New Mexico, is a Spanish-language version
of the Social Security commercial now running there and in 16 other
states.
</P>
<P>
   The ad promises that Bush will not deny benefit to people at or
near retirement, while letting younger workers invest part of their
Social Security taxes in private accounts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000616.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation Bill Deal Sought  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate-passed measure that would establish
the first national standard for drunken driving could hit a
roadblock in the House as negotiators from both chambers try to
adopt a compromise transportation spending bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other contentious issues include a proposal that would cut
operating hours for truckers and a move to allow a study of ways to
improve fuel efficiency for sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The drunken driving provision, which was contained in a $54.7
billion bill the Senate passed on Thursday, would make a 0.08
percent blood alcohol content the allowable limit for drivers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''This reasonable standard will save hundreds of lives and
prevent countless injuries each year and it should be put in place
across the country without further delay,'' President Clinton said
in urging Congress to send him a transportation bill that includes
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., chief advocate of the national
standard, said 0.08 nationwide would save 500 to 700 lives a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the House has blocked past Senate efforts to make the
standard 0.08, which is now the limit in 18 states and the District
of Columbia. The other 32 states have less stringent 0.10 percent
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would deduct a state's federal highway trust
fund share, 5 percent from 2004, if it does not adopt the 0.08
level.
</P>
<P>
   The advocacy group Mothers Against Drunk Driving says the risk
of a fatal crash is 11 times greater from a driver at 0.08 than for
a non-drinking driver. The American Beverage Institute contends
that its more important to get real problem drinkers off the roads
and cites a study finding the risk of an accident for a 0.10 driver
is the same as for a driver using a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would prevent the Transportation Department from
spending federal funds to impose new rules for how many hours a
truck or bus driver may be behind the wheel each day. The House has
proposed no such ban.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue is blamed for a third of the more than 5,000
truck-related fatalities every year. The Transportation Department
has proposed a rule that would limit driving to 12 hours in a
24-hour period. Current rules, dating back more than 60 years,
allow up to 16 hours in one 24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry agrees that the rules must be updated but
claims the proposed rules would result in more accidents because
transport companies would have to hire more novice drivers and
drive in daylight hours when the highways are most crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proposed rule just will not work in the real world,'' said
Jim Whittinghill, senior vice president of the American Trucking
Associations.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said he was ''very
disappointed'' with the ban on rule making. ''The proposed rule
focuses on the critical issue of fatigue, a significant factor in
crashes involving heavy trucks and of saving lives and preventing
injuries on our roadways.''
</P>
<P>
   In another area, it's the House that once again has barred the
Transportation Department from studying whether to raise auto fuel
efficiency standards, particularly on sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The current corporate average fuel economy standards, known as
CAFE, were set in 1975 at 27.5 mpg on new passenger cars and 20.7
mpg for light trucks, which today would include minivans and SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   With new fuel efficiency technology and soaring gas prices,
there is pressure from the Clinton administration and many
lawmakers to change those standards, but the auto industry claims
it would result in smaller, less-safe vehicles, and the House since
1995 has attached language to the transportation spending bill
prohibiting any study of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., won
support for a resolution putting the Senate on record as being for
lifting the study ban but with the condition that Congress must
approve the promulgation of any new fuel efficiency standards. Sen.
Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., and others concerned about effects on the
auto industry agreed to the resolution on the condition the study
also covered vehicle safety and other factors that could affect the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also contains language barring the
administration from issuing any rollover safety rules for SUVs
until the National Academy of Sciences completes a proposed
nine-month study of alleged SUV rollover tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is S. 2720.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   MADD: http://www.madd.org
</P>
<P>
   American Beverage Institute: http://www.abionline.org
</P>
<P>
   American Trucking Associations: www.truckline.com
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety: http://www.saferoads.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
