<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon To Keep Troops in Korea  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The leaders of North and South Korea have
taken a first step toward peace, but the Clinton administration
says it's too early to talk about removing U.S. troops from the
divided peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, public pressure for a reduction in U.S. forces in
South Korea is likely to build if the Koreas actually move toward a
peace treaty, administration officials and outside experts said in
interviews Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what will happen almost overnight,'' said Robert
Riscassi, a retired Army general who commanded U.S. forces in Korea
from 1990-93. ''Clearly there will be a debate. It's inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 37,000 American troops in South Korea, mainly
soldiers of the Eighth Army, headquartered at Yongsan Army Garrison
in Seoul, and airmen of the 7th Air Force, based at Osan Air base.
The United States has maintained a continuous military presence in
South Korea since the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to be very clear that we intend to remain a force for
stability in that area as long as we are needed,'' said Kenneth
Bacon, spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen. Bacon said
the South Korean government has made clear that it expects U.S.
troops to remain ''for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, we don't envision any change in the U.S. troop
status,'' said P.J. Crowley, spokesman for the National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, meanwhile, announced a 50,000-ton
food donation Thursday for North Korea and also offered rare praise
for North Korean President Kim Jong Il for his role in bringing
about this week's historic summit with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman, said the food
donation was long planned and should not be interpreted as a reward
for the breakthroughs achieved at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The food aid brings to 450,000 tons the combined U.S. donations
over the past year through the U.N. World Food Program, which will
assure the deliveries. An additional 100,000 tons was distributed
through a private group.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has been suffering acute food shortages over the
years as a result of drought, flooding and mismanagement of the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kim Jong Il, Boucher said the United States was ''pleased
that North Korea's leader demonstrated practical statesmanship as
he reached agreement with the South's president on a number of
important steps that we think do bode well for the future of the
peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher's statement marked a change in U.S. attitude toward the
North Korean leader, who has acquired few admirers in the West
because of his ruthless repression, attempts to intimidate
neighbors and policies that have contributed to famine.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenly brighter prospect of a Korean peace also has
sparked speculation that the Pentagon's push to build a limited
national defense against missile attack could be slowed. That's
because the potential attacker most prominently mentioned by the
Pentagon is North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the administration welcomed diplomatic progress
toward reducing the ballistic missile threat from North Korea, but
he added that a U.S. missile defense system would be useful against
other countries too.
</P>
<P>
   ''North Korea is not the only country we worry about,'' Bacon
said. ''We worry about Iraq. We worry about Iran, and we worry
about other countries that are working on long-range missiles or
that already have chemical or biological weapons and would like to
have ways to deliver them with long-range missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon acknowledged, however, that the Pentagon's self-imposed
deadline for fielding a missile defense by 2005 was based mainly on
intelligence estimates that North Korea could have a missile
capable of reaching U.S. soil by that time. The CIA has said it
believes Iranian and Iraqi missile threats are farther in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it remains far from clear whether the agreement on
Wednesday by South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean
leader Kim Jong Il to work toward a peaceful reunification of the
divided peninsula will bear fruit. The two sides have been at each
other's throats for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration's view, if the threat of a North
Korean attack on the South disappeared, there would still be reason
to keep U.S. troops on the peninsula -- as a stabilizing influence
in the greater Asia-Pacific region. That is the same reasoning
behind keeping U.S. troops permanently in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Many South Koreans, however, might not see it that way if their
country were reunified with the North. Already there is a push --
small but sometimes forceful -- among South Korean youth to demand a
U.S. withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States, the next step in promoting improved
relations with North Korea will be formal implementation of steps
announced last September to ease sanctions against Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   Once the paperwork is completed, North Korea would be allowed to
export raw materials and goods to the United States and would open
air and shipping routes between the two countries. An announcement
on these measures is expected shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's order would not affect a ban on exports of military
and sensitive dual-use items or most types of federal assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0239 </TRAILER>
