<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Kills Curbs on U.S. Monuments  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is hailing the House's refusal
to limit President Clinton's ability to establish national
monuments as part of his land preservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 204-172 early Friday to approve a $14.6 billion
measure financing the Interior Department and federal cultural
programs for next year. The White House has threatened a veto
because of its 70 percent cut in Clinton's proposal for $620
million to buy federal and local park lands, and reductions in his
plans for clean water, Indian, arts and energy efficiency programs.
</P>
<P>
   But in a win for Clinton and environmentalists, the House voted
to erase language authored by Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, that would
have barred the Interior Department from ''design, planning or
management'' of any national monuments designated since the
beginning of this year. That would have covered eight new monuments
created by Clinton since January and the expansion of a ninth,
covering nearly 2 million acres in Arizona, California, Colorado,
Oregon and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're delighted that the House is preserving this important
tool to protect America's national treasures,'' White House
spokesman Jake Siewert said later.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had objected strongly to the language.
</P>
<P>
   The overall bill was a battleground, as usual, over the National
Endowment for the Arts. And as usual, Republicans seeking to hold
the agency's budget to $98 million -- about the same as this year --
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Endowment proponents led by Reps. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., and
Norm Dicks, D-Wash., won a preliminary 207-204 vote in an effort to
provide an extra $15 million for the arts agency. For a while, it
seemed the endowment would win its first significant increase in
the House since 1992, when its budget peaked at $176 million.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders headed them off by proposing to instead spend
the extra money on Indian health services. Their measure was
approved by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has designated the national monuments under the 1906
Antiquities Act, which allows a president to set aside federal
lands as monuments for historic or scientific reasons. Republicans
said he had used the law to set aside more land than it intended,
was ignoring the will of local members of Congress and other
officials, and was using the designation for election-year
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't have a king with a stroke of a pen designate land,''
said Rep. Randy Cunningham, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides looking ahead to this November's elections, the
fight echoed the numerous environmental battles waged between
Republicans and Clinton since the GOP took control of Congress in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sam Farr, D-Calif., said Clinton had to make the
designations ''because this Congress, under this leadership, is
failing to deliver these things.''
</P>
<P>
   On the pivotal vote, lawmakers voted 234-187 to reject an effort
by Hansen to keep his language intact. Thirty-eight Republicans
joined 195 Democrats and 1 independent in opposing Hansen; 177
Republicans, 9 Democrats and 1 independent voted ''yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The House then voted 243-177 to delete the Hansen provision and
another section of the bill aimed at slowing government efforts to
tighten land-use restrictions in federal lands in the Columbia
River basin in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   That vote came after Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., lost an
effort to protect bill language preventing new management rules in
the basin. That vote was 221-206.
</P>
<P>
   But later, after many lawmakers had gone home, the House
reversed itself and voted 197-180 to restore the Nethercutt
language. The provision would affect a federal effort that began in
1993 involving 63 million acres of federal land in Washington
state, Oregon, Idaho and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has yet to write its own version of the Interior
bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 0259 </TRAILER>
