<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Slips 47; Nasdaq Gains 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading Friday, with
technology shares rising while blue-chip stocks came under selling
pressure after Xerox issued a profit warning.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 47.02 at 10,667.80.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 2.82 at 1,475.78, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 14.57 at 3,860.31.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks got an initial lift from a fresh sign that the Federal
Reserve's six interest rate increases are cooling down a red-hot
economy to what is hoped will be a more sustainable growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported housing construction fell 3.9
percent in May, to its lowest level in nearly a year and weaker
than analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggested that rising mortgage rates are cutting into
demand. That's a direct result of the Fed's inflation-fighting rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   A number of recent economic reports -- including home sales,
factory orders, retail sales and unemployment -- indicate the
economy is cooling down. Given that, a growing number of analysts
believe the Fed will leave interest rates unchanged when its meets
June 27 and 28. But the view is not unanimous and some analysts say
the Fed may still feel that more needs to be done to make sure
inflation is not revived.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street has been hoping for a slower economic growth
rate, market watchers warn that a softer economy could reduce
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Xerox Corp. fell $4.688 to $20.625 in early trading
after the office machine maker said its second-quarter earnings
would fall short of Wall Street analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   While blue-chip stocks were mostly lower, many technology shares
rose. Qualcomm was up $4.063 to $$65.50, bouncing higher after two
days of steep losses.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 298.82 million
shares, well ahead of Thursday's early pace. The double-witching
expiration of stock and index options contributed to the higher
volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index up 1.32 at 513.57.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.12 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.27 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.03 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
