<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mallett Could Succeed Daley  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deputy Commerce Secretary Robert L. Mallett,
the department's No. 2 official, has emerged as one of the top
candidates to succeed William Daley, administration officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision has yet to be made on the next secretary, but
Mallett will take over in an acting capacity when Daley leaves on
July 15. Mallett's name is on a short list of candidates President
Clinton will consider in filling the post permanently, the
officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore announced Thursday that Daley would take
over as manager of Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett has focused on managing day-to-day operations at the
sprawling 40,000-employee Cabinet agency since taking the No. 2
post in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the administration, Mallett, a graduate of
Harvard Law School, practiced law in Washington and served as city
administrator and deputy mayor under former Washington Mayor Sharon
Pratt Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett has canceled a scheduled trip to several countries in
Africa to stay in Washington because of Daley's planned departure,
department spokesman Morrie Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said because of the possible appearance of a
conflict-of-interest, Daley was reassessing how involved he will be
in pushing for Senate approval of legislation for normal trade
relations with China and with other Commerce issues during the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ''The general counsel is looking at all of that to see what he
can and can't do,'' Goodman said. Daley ''wants to be sure that
everything that he does is within the bounds of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about comments by a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott that Daley's departure ''is not helpful'' to efforts to
get the China bill to the Senate floor for a vote, Goodman said,
''There should be a quick vote in the Senate and that should have
nothing to do with whether the secretary is here or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
