<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright To Visit China, So. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
make a hastily arranged trip to China and South Korea next week in
a trip that will take her also to Poland and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's talks in Beijing and Seoul will center on the
historic agreement between the presidents of North and South Korea
to work for peace and unity on the divided peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state leaves Tuesday and plans to arrive in
Warsaw by the weekend for a three-day conference of central
Europe's newly democratic nations, the State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also will go the Middle East, but Boucher did not say
how that stop will fit into a schedule apparently being put
together with uncommon speed.
</P>
<P>
   In China, he said, Albright will take up issues of both
agreement and discord. Referring to Taiwan, which China considers
an irksome, breakaway province, Boucher said, ''We have different
approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   China has good ties with both Koreas and helped arrange the
summit in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, that ended Thursday
with an agreement that asserted a need for reconciliation and
unification. Presidents Kim Dae-jung of South Korea and Kim Jong Il
of North Korea celebrated the pact with champagne toasts.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the accord, Boucher said this week that North
Korea still poses a missile threat to the United States. President
Clinton is considering a national missile-defense system but has
been unable to persuade Russian President Vladimir Putin to amend a
1972 arms control treaty to make it legal.
</P>
<P>
   The warming of relations between North and South Korea also
could have an impact on keeping 37,000 U.S. troops on the peninsula
a half-century after the Korean conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is expected to hold talks in Beijing with Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan on Thursday, but apparently little
else has been decided for her quick visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 1400 </TRAILER>
