<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Rejects U.N. Verification  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Prime Minister Salim Hoss on Friday
rejected U.N. verification of Israel's withdrawal from southern
Lebanon, saying Israeli forces were still in control of some parts
of Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Hoss said Israeli troops still manned several
positions inside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''With deep regret, it appeared by Friday evening that Israel
has not yet withdrawn from all Lebanese territory,'' Hoss said
shortly after U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan told a news
conference in New York that Israel had completely pulled out its
forces from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Lebanese officers working with the U.N. team
inspecting the Lebanese-Israeli border had found ''there are still
several Israeli military outposts inside the Lebanese border. And
there are several tracts of Lebanese territory under Israeli
control in a flagrant act of encroachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that the secretariat-general of the United
Nations would have announced the withdrawal had been completed in
accordance with resolution 425 had it been informed of these
facts,'' Hoss added.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Annan confirmed the withdrawal, Lebanese President
Emile Lahoud warned that his government was opposed to the
U.N.-demarcated frontier and would consider Israel's pullout to be
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's formal declaration of the withdrawal paves the way for
the 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping mission in Lebanon to deploy to
the Lebanese-Israeli border and help the Lebanese government
reassert its authority in the vacated territory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm delighted to tell you that the United Nations force in
Lebanon has today reported to me that Israel has withdrawn from the
country in full compliance with Security Council resolution 425,''
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a happy day for Lebanon but also for Israel,'' Annan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan did not address Lahoud's earlier comments, saying only
that he was heading to the Middle East later Friday to meet leaders
of all sides and ''to see what the United Nations can do to
consolidate and build on today's achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud's warning underlined the Lebanese government's reluctance
to deploy troops in the area that Israel had occupied as a buffer
zone against guerrilla attacks. Beirut had said it will only deploy
military force in the area, where guerrillas are now the de facto
authority, after the United Nations had verified Israel's
withdrawal and deployed peacekeepers along the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, a spokesman for Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Gadi Baltiansky, refused to comment on the verification, saying the
government would respond either late Saturday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel first invaded Lebanon in 1978. It occupied a strip along
the southern Lebanese border as a buffer against attacks on
northern Israel from 1985 until last month.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has promised to boost the U.N. peacekeeping
force in south Lebanon once Israel's withdrawal was verified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
