<HEADLINE> Voting Documents Seized in Zimbabwe  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Militants supporting President Robert
Mugabe have seized identification and voting papers to prevent
suspected opposition supporters from casting ballots in next
month's parliamentary election, human rights groups said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In at least three voting districts, government supporters
destroyed ID cards, passports and other documents in an apparent
effort to intimidate voters ahead of the June 24-25 election, said
David Chimini of Zimbabwe Human Rights Forum, a coalition of
independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   The militants confiscated documents in the central region of
Gokwe, southern Mwenezi and eastern Mutoko, knowing the papers
could not be replaced in time for the polling, said the coalition
of nine legal, church and human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition Movement for Democratic Change also reported
government supporters burning documents in about 30 of the nation's
120 parliamentary districts.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents of arson, beatings, torture, and intimidation have
forced rural voters to seek safety in towns and cities, where they
are not entitled to vote, Chimini said.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion poll published Friday showed the opposition -- which
now holds only three parliamentary seats -- could take as many as 70
slots in the 150-seat parliament. A total of 120 seats will be at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Opinion Institute at the University of Zimbabwe said
it canvassed 6,000 voters across the country and allowed a 10
percent margin of error in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition research coordinator Tony Reeler said unruly
opposition members were also to blame for recent violence. But
their actions bore no comparison to the violence perpetrated by the
ruling party, its agents and members of the secret police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government and its supporters were attempting ''to terrorize
the opposition into submission,'' Reeler said.
</P>
<P>
   Election monitors traced the violence back to February, when
ruling party militants and war veterans began illegally occupying
more than 1,400 white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   Squatter settlements on the farms became bases for intimidating
farmers, their workers and nearby rural poor. At least 31 people,
mostly opposition supporters, have died in political violence since
February.
</P>
<P>
   ''The objective of this campaign has been to smash the
organizational capacity of the opposition,'' Reeler said.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe ordered police not to remove the squatters from farms,
insisting they were protesting unfair land ownership by whites
dating to British colonial rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
