<HEADLINE> Pinochet Attends Funeral of Top Cop  </HEADLINE>
By EVA VERGARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet, walking with
difficulty and using a cane, made a surprise public appearance
Friday to attend funeral services for a former secret police chief
who served under his dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet had not appeared in public since his March 3 return
from British detention, except to make several visits to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Humberto Gordon led Pinochet's secret police from
1980 to 1987, and later joined his ruling junta. He died Thursday
of a heart attack at age 72.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 84, arrived in his usual motorcade of three armored
automobiles to the Military Chapel in western Santiago. Wearing a
cap and a heavy blue overcoat, Pinochet was helped by bodyguards to
step out of the car and walk into the chapel.
</P>
<P>
   He walked with difficulty, but did not use a wheelchair as he
has done in recent weeks. He told reporters in a low voice that he
felt ''well.''
</P>
<P>
   For about five minutes he stayed at the church, talking to
Gordon's widow, Maruja Maturana, and to retired Gen. Rafael
Villarroel, a former close aide.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for radio Cooperativa of Santiago said he overheard
Pinochet tell Villarroel: ''Ones go first, others go later.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon died under house arrest, indicted in five killings that a
judge traced to the security service he once commanded.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet himself has been waging a legal battle to avoid trial
in Chile. He has an appeal pending before the Supreme Court to a
lower court ruling that stripped him of congressional immunity.
</P>
<P>
   In London, he was under house detention for 503 days fighting
extradition to Spain for trial. British authorities released him
after doctors said he was physically and mentally unfit to stand
trial.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official report, 3,190 people were killed under
Pinochet's regime, and more than 1,000 remain unaccounted for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
