<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-Trade Supporters Fear Delay  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proponents of a bill to expand trade with
China expressed increasing alarm that they are losing momentum in
the Senate. It is now unlikely to come up before the Fourth of
July, Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle conceded Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle for the first time even held out the prospect that a
vote might be put off to September. ''It is more likely it will
come up later rather than sooner,'' he told reporters, calling its
chances of passage endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters in both parties suggested Commerce Secretary William
Daley's upcoming departure to run Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign was further complicating the timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, the Clinton administration's point man on the China trade
bill, is leaving his post on July 15 to assume the campaign job.
</P>
<P>
   That ''is not helpful'' to efforts to get the China trade bill
approved, said John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki, responding to Daschle's comments, said Friday that
Lott has not ruled out a vote before the Fourth of July. ''That's
not to say that a vote has been scheduled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that Sen. Daschle is not suggesting that the world's
most deliberative body become a rubber stamp for what the House
does,'' Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   While the legislation itself has wide support, it has become a
victim of political maneuvering in the rush to clear the
legislative decks before this summer's political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Backers so far have been unable to capitalize on the momentum
they thought they had won from last month's larger-than-expected
237-197 victory in the House.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. business leaders, who have much of the lobbying muscle on
behalf of the bill, are now warning legislative leaders that
delaying the vote beyond July could prove disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Donahue, the head of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, met
privately with Lott on Thursday to urge prompt action.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to move this thing as quickly as possible,'' chamber
spokesman Frank Coleman said. ''Everybody knows that at any moment
there are issues that could arise that could complicate matters in
the Congress on this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are blaming Lott for playing politics with the bill --
to gain leverage on other issues and to prolong Democratic
discomfort. ''The majority is playing a very risky game in delaying
this,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor, a key Democratic constituency, strongly opposes
the bill and plans to turn up the heat as elections approach. ''It
is no secret that this is not an easy issue for a lot of Democrats,
for most Democrats,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The South Dakota Democrat also said Daley's departure could have
''significant impact. He has a depth of friendship and credibility
on the Hill that is as great as anybody I know.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have fewer than 35 legislative days remaining in this
Congress,'' Daschle added. ''I think it would be devastating if we
lost PNTR just because we've run out of time. But that is very
possible, especially if we wait until September.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end annual votes on China's status and grant it
permanent normal trading relations (PNTR). U.S. companies could
then take advantage of market-opening concessions China made to
join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hope to keep the bill from being further amended in
the Senate. The House added several provisions, including one for a
human-rights monitoring commission.
</P>
<P>
   Any changes made by the Senate would eventually require another
likely contentious vote in the House -- something proponents clearly
hope to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Amendments have been threatened by Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. And Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said
he will pursue an amendment if he can't get a separate vote on his
bill to impose sanctions on China for weapons proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people want a clean bill, I understand that, but the
Constitution doesn't say anything about our requirement to have a
clean bill. It does require us to take care of matters of national
security,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a top China-trade supporter, will meet
next week with Lott and Daschle to press for a commitment for a
vote in July, said his press secretary, Mike Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   ''His intent is on avoiding a scenario where the most important
Senate vote in a generation slips into the everyday mess of
Washington politics,'' Siegel said. ''In his estimation, it must
happen by the end of July, otherwise it could be lost for this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
