<HEADLINE> Puerto Rican Activist Has Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYAMON, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Ruben Berrios, a key opponent of
U.S. Navy bombing on the island of Vieques, underwent an operation
Friday to remove a cancerous prostate.
</P>
<P>
   Berrios, 60, was the most visible leader of the protesters who
camped out on the U.S. Navy bombing range on Vieques for more than
a year, preventing exercises after an April 1999 accident in which
a civilian guard was killed by two errant bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Berrios' physician, Dr. Mario Maldonado, said Berrios was in
good condition after the surgery and would remain hospitalized for
a day or two for observation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The operation was a success and Ruben is recuperating very
well,'' Maldonado said.
</P>
<P>
   Berrios' wife, Vivian Alemany, said. ''The most important thing
now is rest and recuperation and we're going to work on that.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, federal agents removed more than 200 protesters from
the bombing range and the Navy renewed bombing with non-explosive
''dummy'' bombs a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, Berrios and another activist were detained for
entering the range, and Berrios served a six-hour jail sentence
Tuesday for a federal trespassing conviction. A day later, he
revealed he had prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Berrios, head of the Puerto Rico Independence Party, is running
for governor of Puerto Rico in November elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
