<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Missile Fuel Leak Hurts 10  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLADIVOSTOK, Russia (AP) -- Fuel leaked from a missile as it was
being unloaded from a ship Friday, unleashing a yellow cloud of
toxic fumes that burned the respiratory tracts of 10 Russian
servicemen, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The R-29 missile leaked fuel, which then oxidized when it
touched water and produced a cloud containing nitric acid, said
Irina Andriyanova, spokeswoman for the Emergency Situations
Ministry in the Far East region of Vladivostok. The 1.6
million-square-foot toxic cloud drifted east along the shore toward
Nakhodka, a large port for sea traffic from Japan, Andriyanova
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if the servicemen, employed at a nearby military
base, were on site when the missile was being unloaded. They were
hospitalized, but their conditions were not revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Local radio stations warned nearby residents to stay indoors and
close their windows as the cloud drifted over a small town and out
to sea. No other injuries were reported, and the cloud dissipated
after six hours, Andriyanova said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-stage R-29 is designed to carry a nuclear warhead up to
4,800 miles after launch from a Delta-class submarine. Officials
said the missile's warhead had been removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
