<DOCNO> APW20000616.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fostering fatherhood at heart of state law  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, Conn. (AP) - Louis Mercado used to stay out nights
clubbing. The 19-year-old high school dropout also vowed he would
never change a diaper. But the birth of his daughter changed his
head and his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he helps others like him deal with the challenges of
fatherhood thorough a Norwich agency, which received one of three
$200,000 pilot grants under the state's Fatherhood Initiative law.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of responsibility... a lot of changes. I used
to go out, date girls left and right, but now that she came into my
life, no more going out,'' said Mercado, a Foxwoods Resort Casino
employee.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels good going home and having a daughter come up to you
and give you a hug and say I love you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jada Ashley Mercado arrived, all 9 pounds, 12 ounces of her, on
May 6, 1998 at William W. Backus Hospital in Norwich. Mercado and
Jada's mother, Nicole Bowers, live together and are both working to
support their family. He also has custody of his 12-year-old
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The proud papa is quick to pull out a handful of baby pictures
from his wallet upon request. The photos chronicle Jada's
development from newborn to toddler. Much like his daughter,
Mercado has grown over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He said the full weight of fatherhood hit him when he found out
his girlfriend was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right then, I knew it was my responsibility to keep her
healthy and all that,'' said Mercado, who participated in a panel
discussion at a conference on fatherhood Friday in Norwch.
</P>
<P>
   He finds support at Madonna Place, a downtown Norwich social
agency. It was one of three organizations to receive a $200,000
two-year grant from the state's Fatherhood Initiative, a program
designed to help noncustodial fathers stay involved in their
children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Other grant recipients were Families in Crisis, a program
targeting young fathers at the state prison in Cheshire and Career
Resources, a Bridgeport-based program that stresses education,
training and employment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Department of Social Services, about 23
percent of all households have no father and more than half of
those are impoverished. Nationally, about 17 million homes are
fatherless. Connecticut is one of several states adopting
fatherhood initiatives, a relatively new concept since most job and
family related services for low-income people are directed to
women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have one of the most comprehensive pieces of
legislation on this issue,'' said Social Services Commissioner Pat
Wilson-Coker.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the money was another matter, she said. Enacted during
the 1999 General Assembly, the fatherhood law landed on
Wilson-Coker's desk with virtually no money to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like I've always said, 'vision is free.' I was told I could
find $100,000 in my budget and I did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, lawmakers appropriated $600,000 for the three grants.
To be eligible for the grants, the organizations had to show they
had something built into their programs that would sustain them
after the grants ran out, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They also had to prove they were connected to the community,''
said Wilson-Coker.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna Place has been tied to Norwich for 13 years and has just
moved to larger building. About three dozen men attend the agency's
parenting groups, according to staff member and group leader Gary
Hotham. He said the fathers range from late teens to the forties in
age and many, said Hotham, bring their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Louis has been one of the foundations of our Friday group.
He's been a rock for the other guys,'' said Hotham. ''They all turn
to jelly when they start passing Jada around. It's great to see
these guys experience that paternal instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   They also share in each other's sorrow, said Mary Mason, who is
affiliated with Madonna Place. She said one group member recently
lost touch with his child when the mother moved out of state and
left no address.
</P>
<P>
   ''To see our young dad still coming to the group and (he's) so
sad without his baby ... it's heartbreaking,'' she said. ''We see
it when it gets severed and how painful it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercado is trying to break the cycle he grew up with. He never
knew his father and his only male role models were cousins, who now
live out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been pretty much developing by myself,'' he said. ''I'm
getting there ... hopefully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1644 </TRAILER>
