<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of a new television ads from Hillary Rodham Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of Senate candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton's new
television advertisements:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLES: ''News Update: HMOs'' and ''News Update: Hate Crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 15 seconds each.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Team Hillary, the Clinton campaign advertising group
that includes media guru Mandy Grunwald.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Statewide starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPTS: ''Update: The Senate just voted to kill the Patients'
Bill of Rights ....by two votes. Hillary supports it. In the House,
Rick Lazio voted against the bill ... siding with the Republican
leadership. Rick Lazio ... the more you know ... the more you
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Update: The state Senate just passed tougher penalties for
hate crimes. Hillary fought for the bill. Rick Lazio was opposed.
But five days after it passed, he flip-flopped. The Post called it
an ''about face.'' Rick Lazio ... the more you know ... the more
you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Both ads feature a typewriter sound in the background as
the words the narrator is reading appear in white letters on a
black screen.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: The ads echo a new campaign strategy in which Clinton
is trying to portray issues-oriented differences between herself
and Republican Rep. Rick Lazio. She began on Tuesday in Westchester
County, questioning Lazio's commitment to hate crimes laws that
increase penalties in cases where there is gay bias or other forms
of discrimination. She also criticized Lazio for opposing the White
House-backed version of the patients' bill of rights, which would
give patients the right to sue health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he voted against the health care bill because he
believes it will benefit lawyers rather than patients. He says he
supports the hate crimes law that passed in the state Senate, but
abstained in 1990 while serving in the Suffolk County Legislature
on a measure calling for a hate crimes law to be enacted in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The tag line ''Rick Lazio ... the more you know ... the more you
wonder,'' seems to be the mantra the campaign will use in its bid
to define the little-known Long Island congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   AdWatch analysis by Frank Eltman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
