<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton chides Republicans on school construction funds  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - On a hot school playground in Queens, President
Clinton blasted House Republicans for zeroing out his request for
more than $1 billion to renovate the nation's dilapidated schools
and ease overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we think that we're going to build the future of our dreams
by making these kids go to school in places where they don't have
computer labs, they don't have music rooms ... their buildings are
being heated with coal and their teachers are trying to teach 40
kids when they ought to be teaching 20, we're living in a dream
world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke in front of three temporary classroom trailers
decorated with red-white-and-blue tissue paper flowers and signs
welcoming the president. He implored parents, students and teachers
crowded on the playground to push Congress to appropriate funds and
ask lawmakers: ''Where is the bill? Show me the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The House passed an appropriations bill on Wednesday that left
out the president's request for $1.3 billion in grants and loans to
support an estimated $6.5 billion in repairs and renovations to the
most dilapidated schools.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans fear it would create unnecessary bureaucracy
in Washington. They don't want the federal government to meddle in
local school district affairs, said Becky Campoverde, spokeswoman
for House Education and Workforce Committee Chairman Rep. Bill
Goodling, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's prefers a tax credit plan like one Clinton vetoed last
year, she said, when Congress aimed to lower a school district's
cost of borrowing money for building projects.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton disagrees. ''Some people say 'Let them do it at the
local level,''' he said. ''We've got more kids in school than ever
before, but we've got a smaller percentage of taxpayers and it's
hard, if not impossible, to raise the money to build and repair
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is happier with a Senate measure, which includes $3.1
billion for a block grant program that school districts could use
for school construction and other projects to reduce class size and
train teachers. But he wants a specific program for school
construction because there's no guarantee the money would be used
to fix schools in serious disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the General Accounting Office, Congress'
investigative arm, said the cost to build new schools and modernize
old ones is at least $112 billion, and more recent estimates say it
will cost much more. A GAO survey of 10,000 schools in 1995 found
one-third needed extensive repair or replacement of one or more
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our English language learners are taught in the hall,'' said
Mary Minnick, who began teaching at Abigail Adams when Lyndon
Johnson was president. ''Our science teachers are bag ladies,
carrying their wares from room to room.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton visited a public elementary school
in East Harlem, where he spoke on NBC's ''Today'' show to support
the ''Save the Music'' program. Time Warner Cable and the VHI Save
The Music Foundation began it in 1997 to support music education in
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a saxophone player in his high school band, said music
programs are often the first to go when budgets are cut. In its
first year, the program collected more than $1 million in
instruments for music education in New York City. The program is
working to expand to 40 communities in 23 states, the District of
Columbia and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, Clinton was to speak at an evening fund raiser for
Rep. Edolphus Towns, D-N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1734 </TRAILER>
