<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union opposes psychiatric hospital takeover plan  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Labor unions, upset over the
consolidation of the Yale Psychiatric Institute into the
university's hospital, are accusing a state official of improperly
changing the terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling by the Office of Health Care Access means the hospital
will close 11 beds for adult psychiatric patients at a time when
demand for psychiatric services is surging, the Federation of
Hospital and University Employees claims.
</P>
<P>
   Yale-New Haven Hospital, which is taking over the university-run
psychiatric institute, maintains that beds are not closing and
services will improve under the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The union claims that Health Care Access Commissioner Raymond
Gorman had improper communication with Yale that led to a revision
of the terms of the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The union has filed a formal complaint with the agency, seeking
to reopen the process that led to Gorman's decision. They have
asked Gorman to recuse himself from the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman stood by his ruling Friday and said he did nothing
improper in clarifying his order at Yale-New Haven Hospital's
request. The union is not a formal party to the proceeding, so they
did not have to be in on the talks, Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorman also said he was skeptical of the hospital's plans
and would monitor carefully to see if more beds are needed for
psychiatric patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an extraordinary crisis in behavioral health right
now,'' Gorman said. ''The last thing I want to do is eliminate beds
unless I'm absolutely sure an appropriate mechanism has been put
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The union maintains Gorman's clarification fundamentally changed
the terms of the deal, said Mark Herz, a psychiatric assistant at
Yale Psychiatric Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's trying to sing two tunes at once out of one mouth,'' Herz
said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the number of beds available in New Haven for adult
psychiatric patients, and how and where they should be treated.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Yale Psychiatric Institute and Yale-New Haven
Hospital have 92 licensed psychiatric beds.
</P>
<P>
   Yale Psychiatric Institute is licensed for 66 beds, but on a
daily basis it houses an average of 55 patients, leaving an average
of 11 vacant beds. Yale-New Haven Hospital has 26 psychiatric beds
and houses 24 psychiatric patients on an average day.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital maintains the combined entity can provide good
services with 76 beds, because it also plans to increase day
treatment and outpatient treatment services for psychiatric
patients who would be better off at home than in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman's ruling required the hospital to operate with 81 beds,
until it could prove that it could operate with only 76.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very skeptical that they can do with 76 beds what has
historically taken 81 to 84,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Health Care Access plans to review the situation
in September to see how many beds are needed. If the hospital wants
to go below 81 beds, the agency will hold more public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The union, however, maintains the ruling cuts out the 11 beds
that are currently licensed but not always used at Yale Psychiatric
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Herz pointed out that 55 is an average number of patients -
sometimes there are less and sometimes there are more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have 66 licensed beds, and we accommodate that many people
sometimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokeswoman Katie Krouss said the Yale Psychiatric
Institute rarely had more than 55 patients at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're comfortable the level and quality and amount of care
we're providing will meet the needs of the New Haven population,''
Krouss said.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents clerical workers and aides, also is
upset that its members could lose their jobs to workers from the
hospital, who are not unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Krouss said Yale Psychiatric Institute workers can apply for
jobs with the expanded day treatment programs. Neither the day
programs or the combined facility, to be called Yale-New Haven
Psychiatric Services, will be unionized, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1740 </TRAILER>
