<DOCNO> APW20000616.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil rights finding against NYPD hailed by police critics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Civil rights activists and police critics
applauded a federal commission's finding Friday that the New York
Police Department uses racial profiling, saying it gives them
ammunition to push for outside oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It confirms what many of us have been saying all along - that
racial discrimination by cops is reality for people of color in
this city,'' said the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the department's ''stop and frisk'' tactics, the
report found that blacks and Hispanics were stopped far out of
proportion to their representation in a given community.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton - the organizer of countless protests accusing police
of singling out minorities for abuse - predicted the U.S.
Commission on Civil Right's recommendation for independent
prosecutors and monitors to handle disciplinary cases and civilian
complaints would pave the way for federal oversight of the nation's
largest police force.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a separate ongoing investigation by Brooklyn U.S.
Attorney Loretta Lynch into whether the NYPD fosters abuse of
minorities through lax discipline of officers who use excessive
force. The investigation was launched in 1997 after white patrolmen
were charged with torturing a black prisoner, Abner Louima, with a
broken broomstick in a precinct bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The city and Lynch's office have been negotiating over possible
reforms - a process aimed at avoiding a federal lawsuit against the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton criticized Lynch on Friday for ''moving way too slow.''
One of Louima's attorneys in his $155 million lawsuit against the
city agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, Sanford Rubenstein, noted Louima himself went
before the commission to call for stricter discipline of wayward
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we have an official commission saying there is a problem
in New York,'' the lawyer said. ''Clearly, it's clearly time for
the federal government to intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lynch, William Muller, refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, meanwhile, continued to insist that the
commission's criticisms are inaccurate and overblown, and that the
department is capable of policing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding a 700-page rebuttal to a draft of the report last
month, Police Commissioner Howard Safir insisted the NYPD does not
engage in racial profiling. He argued that the ethnic breakdown of
those stopped and frisked corresponds closely to the ethnic
breakdown of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing remarks by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Safir called the
final draft released Friday ''shoddy.'' He said the commission
should have incorporated his data to balance its report.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, they obviously are too lazy or not skilled enough to
do so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New York Civil Liberties Union president Norman Siegel called on
city officials to ''stop the denials and stop minimizing the
problem of police conduct and failed community relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, Siegel said, ''told it like it is. It appears to
document the painful reality that there are serious problems with
enormous racial overtones. Hopefully, it will be a catalyst for
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1752 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000616.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Briefed on Korean Summit  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- During the historic Korean summit this week,
South Korea's president stressed to North Korea that development of
a nuclear weapons or missile program would be contrary to the
reconciliation the two nations agreed to seek, a senior Clinton
administration official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Kim Dae-jung did bring up the concern about the
possibility or the threat of development of either nuclear or
missile programs and stressed that he thought that they were
destabilizing,'' the official said in recounting what President
Clinton was told in a 25-minute meeting in New York with Hwang
Won-Tak, a senior South Korean security official.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Clinton's plan to ease sanctions
against North Korea, announced last September, will take effect
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Richard Boucher withheld comment on timing of the
announcement, but it appeared to be an effort to build on the
momentum generated by the Pyongyang summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced the relaxation of sanctions last September in
exchange for a North Korean pledge not to test a long-range missile
capable of reaching U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will permit North Korea to export raw materials and
goods to the United States and will open air and shipping routes
between the two countries. For 50 years, virtually all U.S. trade
and financial transactions with North Korea have been banned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Washington, Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said he was encouraged by the new
overtures although it was ''too early to tell'' whether the status
of the 37,000 U.S. troops in South Korea should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's a temporary lull, we'll have to leave the people there
for a while. But if it's for real...then we ought to make plans to
bring those folks home,'' Helms told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official who briefed reporters in New York
said the South Korean leader told North Korea's Kim Jong Il that if
he was interested in reconciliation and eventual reunification of
the Korean Peninsula, his nation must stay away from nuclear or
missile programs ''because that was contrary to the general
atmosphere that the two were trying to create with the summit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the summit, Kim Dae-jung disclosed that he and Kim Jong Il
had discussed sensitive security issues, including the 37,000 U.S.
soldiers stationed in the South and the North's nuclear and missile
programs. He did not describe in detail what they talked about,
however, saying only that the talks were frank and productive.
</P>
<P>
   At the summit, which ended Wednesday, North and South Korea
signed an accord promising to work for eventual reunification and
pledging to allow separated families to meet. The pact also calls
for South Korean investment in impoverished North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The impression was that there were not a lot of specifics that
were discussed there, but that they did agree to further talks at
the ministerial level to flesh out how to implement that
cooperation,'' the administration official said. ''And they also
talked about how President Kim Jong Il agreed to make a visit to
Seoul, although no specific time was established on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call to Clinton Thursday night, the South Korean
leader said that he was well received by the North Koreans. That
message was reiterated in New York by Hwang, who said South Korea
viewed the summit as the ''beginning of an opening up,'' the
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president said he found the account fascinating,'' he
said. ''He found it on balance to be hopeful and agreed that it was
important that the United States and South Korea, along with Japan
and our other friends, consult closely on next steps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
