<HEADLINE> Millville hospital closing in South Jersey Health consolidation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILLVILLE, N.J. (AP) - South Jersey Health System is closing its
Millville hospital as part of a consolidation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, which posted operating losses of $3 million last
year, will close its doors by year's end. South Jersey Health
System officials plan to sell the building to Filmore Street LLC.,
a developer of senior citizen housing.
</P>
<P>
   The closing is part of the company's plan to consolidate its
three Cumberland County hospitals - in Millville, Bridgeton and
Vineland - into one new hospital to be built in Vineland.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation will save $3 million annually, according to
Chester B. Kaletkowski, president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ''The savings will come from streamlining operations and
consolidating services,'' Kaletkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other New Jersey hospitals, the Millville hospital has been
struggling, according to Kerry McKean Kelly, spokeswoman for the
New Jersey Hospital Association, in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hospitals are under fire to become more efficient, with
managed care dictating shorter hospital stays, federal Medicare
cuts, the expense of caring for the uninsured and the state's
shortfall in reimbursing for charity care,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
