<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Meet Croatian Pres.  </HEADLINE>
By EUGENE BRCIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- A delegation of Chinese leaders opened
talks with the Croatian president and other top officials Friday
aimed at expanding trade and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 business officials accompanied Li Peng -- president of
the Chinese parliament and the second most influential figure in
the Chinese Communist Party -- in his five-day visit to Croatia. The
trip is part of larger Eastern European tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''Croatia and China have good bilateral relations, but it is
necessary to further develop economic links,'' Croatian President
Stipe Mesic's office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia was particularly interested in cooperation in the
pharmaceutical, tourism and maritime industries, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Li said China would be looking at ways to expand trade with
Croatia, and said the former Yugoslav republic could expect Chinese
support for its aspirations toward joining mainstream Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in neighboring Slovenia, where Li's visit earlier was
clouded by protests against China's human rights policy, the
meetings in Croatia went by without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a few small articles in local newspapers, the only
real protest came from Croatia's Amnesty International office.
''Such talks must be a chance to improve human rights in any
country,'' Amnesty said in a statement. ''There are no
'untouchable' countries when it comes to human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In Slovenia, about 50 human rights activists demonstrated
outside the Slovenian parliament against China's suppression of
dissent in Tibet and other human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Li canceled a meeting with Slovene Prime Minister Andrej Bajuk,
apparently because the Slovene Cabinet includes the head of a local
pro-Taiwan group. Taiwan and China split in 1949 after the
Communists seized power on the mainland, and China considers Taiwan
a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   Li's delegation was expected to visit the southern resort town
of Dubrovnik this weekend, and then to travel to Slovakia,
Azerbaijan and Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
