<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge awards Ronettes $2.6 million in lawsuit against Phil Spector  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge Friday awarded the Ronettes, a
1960s girl group, $2.6 million in royalties and interest that
members should have received for recordings made for ''boy genius''
producer Phil Spector.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Paula Omansky found that Spector,
who kept the rights to all Ronettes recordings, made millions of
dollars in ways not authorized by his 1963 contract, while paying
the three women nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ronettes received one payment of $14,482.30 - as a group -
for their work under the five-year contract, Omansky said. One of
the women testified that this was the only money they ever received
from Spector.
</P>
<P>
   In her 24-page decision, the judge said ''Defendants (Spector
and his company) acted in complete disregard of plaintiffs'
(Ronettes') rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Omansky said the contract covers only royalties on sales of
phonograph records, but Spector sold the recordings for use as
background music in movies, videocassette recordings, and
advertising. For example, ''Be My Baby'' was used with the opening
credits of the movie ''Dirty Dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Omansky said the contract does not say he can do this, but if he
does, he must give the singers 50 percent of the money. Experts
testified at trial in 1998 that half was the current ''custom and
practice'' for sharing that income.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the judge said, Spector licensed without authority
the group's master recordings to third parties for re-recording -
in ''oldies'' compilations, for example, that also featured other
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Spector relied on contract language which said all recordings
under the contract ''shall be entirely our property, free of any
claims whatsoever by you or any persons deriving any rights of
interest from you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Omansky said an appeals court rejected a similar stance in
another case. She said the court found that the language should be
read to exclude, rather than authorize, uses other than those
stated in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   When Spector discovered the group in 1963, it included two
teen-aged sisters, Veronica and Estelle Bennett, and their
20-year-old cousin, Nedra Talley. On May 6, 1963, Spector and the
group signed a five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Ronettes recorded 28 songs for Spector's Phillies Records
between 1963 and 1967. Their recording of ''Be My Baby'' hit No. 1
on Billboard magazine's pop music charts, and they had some lesser
successes.
</P>
<P>
   The women sued Spector 13 years ago, saying he had cheated them,
and the case went to trial before Omansky in Manhattan's State
Supreme Court in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica ''Ronnie'' Bennett Greenfield, for whom the group was
named, issued a statement Friday. ''I am so glad it's finally
over,'' the statement read by husband Jonathan Greenfield said.
''Maybe now I can get back to doing what I love - making records
and performing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I worked very hard making those records in the '60s,'' her
statement went on. ''I didn't know I'd have to wait 37 years to get
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedra Talley Ross, who lives in Virginia Beach, Va., and owns an
import-export business, said, ''It's been a long time coming.
Justice is what we wanted, and I think we got justice. God is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ronettes' lawyer, Alexander Peltz, said the decision is
important because it is ''the first strong New York decision which
recognizes current custom and practice in revenue sharing, and acts
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peltz said he expects Spector to appeal. Spector's lawyer,
Andrew Bart, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Omansky said the women are entitled to one half of $3.35 million
that Spector got from commercial uses that were not covered by the
contract, plus $925,907 in interest, for a total of about $2.6
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1807 </TRAILER>
