<HEADLINE> Turkish Court Sentences Extremists  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A Turkish court on Friday handed death
sentences to 33 people convicted of seeking to impose Islamic rule
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from a 1993 arson attack that killed 37
left-wing intellectuals at a hotel in the central city of Sivas.
The group had gathered to commemorate a 16th-century poet hanged
for opposing religious oppression.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers barred firefighters from the scene and chanted
slogans associated with Islamic extremism as the hotel burned.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second trial for the accused, ordered after an
appeals court determined that the defendants' identities had not
been sufficiently documented.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is officially secular, although predominantly Muslim. It
has not carried out an execution since 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
