<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine has 10-point lead in early Senate poll  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - In the first poll since the U.S. Senate
primary elections, more New Jersey voters said they would support
Democratic nominee Jon Corzine, but voters still have plenty to
learn about both Corzine and Republican Bob Franks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Neither candidate is well known by the New Jersey electorate,
which means there is a lot of potential for movement before the
election,'' Cliff Zukin, a Rutgers professor and director of the
Star-Ledger/Eagleton-Rutgers Poll, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we're trying to do with this survey is to say here's where
the candidates are at the beginning of the election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the starting gate, Franks is behind.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine leads the congressman from Union County, 43 percent to
33 percent, according to the telephone survey of 618 registered
voters conducted June 8-13.
</P>
<P>
   Among those most likely to vote, Corzine's lead is only 7
percentage points, within the poll's margin of error of plus or
minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   And, there's still plenty of room for movement.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 percent of respondents said they might change their
mind between now and November, and only 23 percent said they were
''very sure'' about Corzine, compared with 19 percent for Franks.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggests that Corzine's unprecedented $34 million
primary spending blitz won him the name recognition the former
Goldman Sachs chairman was seeking. In comparison, Franks spent
$1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' campaign said the first poll is encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is surprising that, given the fact that Corzine outspent
Franks 20 to 1, that we're only 7 points behind,'' said Charlie
Smith, Franks' campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon Corzine just finished spending $34 million and has failed
to reach 50 percent on the ballot test,'' Smith added. ''I think it
demonstrates there's a significant amount of concern among
independents and Republicans regarding Jon Corzine.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's campaign discounted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''A poll taken this early in the general election campaign is
largely irrelevant,'' said Steven Goldstein, Corzine's former
campaign manager who is now acting as a consultant to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously we're happy that Jon has a lead and we're confident
that Jon's lead has the potential for significant growth as he
talks about fiscal responsibility throughout the fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of those polled said they knew ''a lot'' or ''some''
about Corzine. Only 44 percent had no opinion of him - an unusually
low number for this early in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, 72 percent knew ''little'' or ''nothing'' about
Franks.
</P>
<P>
   That indicates the power of Corzine's television ads. By
contrast, Franks, who has represented New Jersey in congress for
nearly eight years, has gotten little media attention in a state
with no network TV station that consistently covers state news.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad, but that's where people get their information,''
said Zukin. ''(Corzine) put on 3,700 spots. It's remarkable. It
sure produces weird dynamics in the state and how it makes
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll also indicated more negative sentiment about Corzine,
with 20 percent saying they had an unfavorable opinion of him. Only
6 percent said they didn't like Franks.
</P>
<P>
   That could help Franks, Zukin said, as long as he's able to
raise enough money to get out his moderate message and contrast it
with Corzine's more liberal one.
</P>
<P>
   ''Franks doesn't have to spend as much as Corzine, but he has to
raise enough money - at least $12 (million) to $15 million - to get
clear messages out to voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to criticisms that Corzine is spending too much, he
recently announced he is reducing his staff by 51 workers, leaving
17 full-time employees. That will cut his monthly staff payroll
from about $1.1 million to $164,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not known how much money the multimillionaire plans
to spend in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine handily defeated former Gov. Jim Florio in the
Democratic primary. Franks emerged from a four-way Republican race
by a slim margin over state Sen. William Gormley. Corzine and
Franks are seeking the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Democrat
Frank Lautenberg, who will retire at the end of his term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
