<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness pleads for mercy for convicted killer in boy witness case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A jury deciding whether Russell Peeler
should get the death penalty for the murders of an 8-year-old boy
witness and his mother began deliberations on Friday but did not
reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler, 28, was convicted last week in the 1999 slayings of
Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke. The same
jury must now decide if Peeler gets life in prison or the death by
lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began considering the case at about 2:30 p.m. after
receiving instruction on the law from Judge G. Sarsfield Ford. The
panel went home for the weekend at 5 p.m. without reaching a
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of hours of deliberations, the jury asked the
judge to repeat his earlier instruction on the legal definition of
committing an offense in an especially heinous, cruel or depraved
manner. That is one of the so-called aggravating factors claimed by
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In their deliberations, jurors must weigh aggravating factors
against mitigating factors presented by the defense in deciding
whether Peeler should get the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The judge explained that in order to find that Peeler committed
the crimes in an especially cruel manner, they must decide either
that Peeler engaged in intentional conduct that inflicted extreme
physical or psychological pain or torture or that he acted in a
callous or indifferent manner to the extreme pain that was
inflicted as a result of his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that Peeler ordered his brother, Adrian, to
kill B.J. and his mother to stop the boy from testifying against
him in an earlier murder case.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued a dozen mitigating factors, including: that
Russell Peeler, while a conspirator, had a relatively limited role
in the killings; that he is already serving a life sentence on
federal drug charges; that he lost his mother to cancer in 1993;
and that he was influenced by the violent subculture of inner-city
life and ''gangsta rap'' music.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is scheduled to resume its deliberations Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1837 </TRAILER>
