<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA proposes eight-year, $92 million cleanup of Ciba site  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - Federal environmental officials have
proposed an eight-year, $92 million plan to clean up contaminated
soil and buried toxins at the former Ciba-Geigy Corp. Superfund
site, which came under scrutiny after an unusually high rate of
childhood cancers was reported here.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal recommended by the Environmental Protection Agency
for the 1,350-acre site calls for excavating about 145,000 cubic
yards of soil and treating it at a building on the site, according
to Romona Pezzella, EPA project manager.
</P>
<P>
   During the treatment, called bioremediation, bacteria that exist
naturally in the dirt would be stimulated to feed on toxins and
speed up their decomposition.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also recommends removing about 35,000 drums of
waste material buried there and an additional 5,000 cubic yards of
contaminated soil, and treating the chemicals offsite.
</P>
<P>
   The two cleanup procedures would remove about 90 percent of the
underground pollutants and protect groundwater from future
contamination, Pezzella said.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents of Toms River blame Ciba-Geigy, now called Ciba
Specialty Chemical Co., for exposing the town to traces of dye and
nitrobenzene that seeped into three wells used by the Toms River
Water Co., which is now known as United Water Toms River.
</P>
<P>
   Organic dyes, epoxy resins and specialty chemicals were
manufactured for nearly 40 years on the site, which was formerly
known as Toms River Chemical Co. Solid and liquid waste from the
manufacturing was dumped in 20 different places at the site,
contaminating soil and ground water.
</P>
<P>
   Declared a federal Superfund site in 1982, the land has come
under increased scrutiny since 1996, when the state revealed an
unusually high rate of some childhood cancers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   After soliciting public comment, the EPA will officially select
a plan to clean up the site. Engineers will spend about two years
drawing up specific treatment plans, Pezzella said. It will take
another eight years, at an estimated cost of $92 million, to
complete the actual cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Ciba Specialty Chemical, based in Tarrytown, N.Y., will pay the
entire cost of the operation and is currently working on a separate
groundwater cleanup that began in 1996, according to company
spokeswoman Donna Jakubowski.
</P>
<P>
   Residents attended a meeting Thursday night to review the
proposal. Other meetings are scheduled for June 22 and July 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased that they selected the alternative that
they did,'' Jakubowski said of the EPA. ''We're happy that it's
acceptable to the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
