<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Sets Date For Pres. Election  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Parliament on Friday set Oct. 8, as the
date for the country's third presidential election since the
collapse of communist rule a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The early favorite is President Aleksander Kwasniewski, who
already has launched his campaign for a second term. An
ex-communist who defeated incumbent Lech Walesa for the post in
1995, Kwasniewski has become Poland's most popular politician, with
poll approval ratings of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His closest challenger, according to recent surveys, is maverick
economist Andrzej Olechowski, who has support of about 10 percent
of voting-age Poles. He has served in the Cabinets of both leftist
and rightist governments in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Walesa, founder of the Solidarity movement that toppled Poland's
communist regime, has said he will run again. His successor as head
of the Solidarity trade union, Marian Krzaklewski, also is running.
Both have been getting poll ratings of less than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have said they will run include a radical farm
leader, Andrzej Lepper, and Kazimierz Switon, a Catholic activist.
</P>
<P>
   Under Poland's democratic constitution, the country elects a
president every five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 1844 </TRAILER>
