<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Fires Brought Under Control  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- The worst fires in Cyprus in more than 30
years have been brought under control, a chief firefighter said
Friday, after the four-day blaze had devastated huge tracts of
land.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the major blazes are out, but we are still on full alert
in case of fresh flare-ups from still smoldering pockets during the
night,'' Fire Service chief George Hajigergiou said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighting aircraft from Greece, Israel and the British
military bases on the island played a major role in containing the
fires, dousing them with tons of water.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Cypriot firefighters and villagers as well as scores
of fire engines worked through the night Thursday and all day
Friday to extinguish the blazes that were boosted by strong winds.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers cleared strips of ground to prevent the fires from
spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Two Israeli helicopters and two water-carrying aircraft from
Greece arrived Thursday following an appeal from the Cyprus
government, joining three helicopters from the British bases in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 fires blazed simultaneously in different parts of
the island earlier in the week, raising suspicions of arson.
</P>
<P>
   President Glafcos Clerides, who visited the worst fire front
Thursday, said an investigation has been ordered. ''Nothing is
ruled out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of acres of forest and agricultural land have been
burned, but there has been no official damage estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture and Environment Minister Costas Agathocleous said
the fires were the worst in more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
