<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Supreme Court delays convicted cop killer's release  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Supreme Court agreed Friday to
keep a cop killer in prison while the Attorney General argues
against his parole.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court said Thomas Trantino deserves to be released after
37 years in state prison for killing two Lodi police officers.
</P>
<P>
   On June 9 the appellate panel ordered Trantino transferred to a
half way house and gave the state Corrections Department 30 days to
prepare him for release.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman immediately ordered Attorney General John
J. Farmer, Jr. to appeal. Farmer's deputies were able to convince
an appeals court judge to grant the emergency stay the day the
opinion was released.
</P>
<P>
   But the same panel that ordered Trantino's release would only
give the state seven days to get the Supreme Court to hear an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the high court said it would hear the state's petition
for the justices to consider the case.
</P>
<P>
   A two-page order signed by Associate Justice Gary S. Stein
delayed the order to release Trantino but offered no reason.
</P>
<P>
   The order came after the request was ''duly considered by the
court,'' Stein wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pleased that the Supreme Court granted a state in this
case while it takes a close look at the actions of the Parole
Board,'' said Roger Shatzkin, a spokesman for Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer alleges that the Parole Board was right to deny
Trantino's release especially since some said he becomes agitated
by stress and had no clear plans for life after prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court set July 5 as the date to decide if it will
hear the full appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino will remain in a state prison until at least that date.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Roger Lowenstein said last week it was unlikely that the
full court will hear the case. A woman who answered the phone at
Lowenstein's home in Vermont said he was traveling and unavailable
for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino, who was convicted of killing two Lodi police officers
in 1963, has been denied parole at least nine times during his 37
years behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel said in a 66-page opinion that Trantino's
latest rejection by the state parole board was ''not supported by
any credible evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Trantino had been sentenced to die for killing the two officers
in a bar in August 1963. But when New Jersey's death penalty was
overturned in 1972, Trantino's sentence was changed to life in
prison. Sentencing guidelines in effect at the time made Trantino
eligible for parole in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   After an earlier appeal, Trantino earned another chance at
release and a hearing before the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   At a June 1999 session, the board rejected Trantino's plea for
parole. Board members relied on a number of points, including
claims by prison mental health examiners that he would likely
commit another crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Trantino argued on appeal that parole board members ignored
several key points on his behalf. Trantino cited a prison record
that showed no infractions since 1970 and a report from a private
doctor and other tests that said he appeared to be a good candidate
for parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
