<HEADLINE> NATO Troops Find Ammunition Depots  </HEADLINE>
By FISNIK ABRASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KLECKA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo's NATO-led peacekeepers on
Friday found a huge stockpile of ammunition stored in two bunkers
that were stacked to the ceiling with grenades, mortars and other
ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers did not know who the weapons belonged to, but the
commander of the search operation suggested the find could be
linked to anti-Serb extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly somebody ... has spent an awful lot of money and
energy setting up this site,'' said Lt. Col. David Allfrey, a
spokesman for the British forces serving in the NATO force. ''What
their designs are, it's not my position to say, but there have been
a few killings in the Serb community in the last couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A year of persistent anti-Serb violence has increased recently,
leading to growing fears among the remaining Kosovo Serb minority.
Serbs have been targeted by ethnic Albanians seeking revenge for
the crackdown on Albanians that ended a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The find was part of an exhaustive search for weapons which
began Thursday and involved hundreds of peacekeepers who covered
about 40 square miles of the Drenica Valley region of central
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Tom Rees, of the British contingent that found the two
concrete bunkers near Klecka, approximately 20 miles southwest of
Pristina, said they contained large numbers of grenades, mortar
rounds and other explosives. He said a more thorough search would
be needed to take full inventory. The storage rooms, which measured
10 yards by four yards by two yards high, were filled to their
ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Klecka was one of the strongholds of the Kosovo Liberation Army
during its battle against President Slobodan Milosevic's forces
that ended last year with the arrival of NATO forces into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A military training area near the bunkers appeared to be
well-kept. There were fresh footprints in the area, according to
NATO personnel on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clearly been used for training, there is a very large
quantity of ammunition,'' Allfrey said. The search commander
suggested that they expected to find even more arms, saying there
appeared to be tunnels leading to other depots nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA was formally disbanded last fall as part of the
demilitarization of Kosovo. But rumors persist that it continues
clandestine operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 1926 </TRAILER>
