<DOCNO> APW20000616.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman very much alive despite Social Security snafu  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WALLKILL, N.Y. (AP) - Dorothy Hunt-Ingrassia is alive and well
despite a federal foul-up that insisted she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   In April, two months of Social Security benefits disappeared
from her bank account. In May, she started getting Medicare bills
addressed to her ''estate.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a face-to-face interview at the Social Security office
to persuade the government that Hunt-Ingrassia, 70, was still among
the living.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, last week, Medicare sent a statement to
Hunt-Ingrassia's estate indicating it had paid for a mammogram.
Stranger still was the note on the bill that Medicare would pick up
the tab for another mammogram in 12 months: A mammogram for
somebody the government thinks is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God I don't live on Social Security alone,''
Hunt-Ingrassia told the Times Herald-Record of Middletown. ''It
would have devastated me.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Social Security Administration thought she had
moved to Las Vegas. In April, U.S. Rep. Ben Gilman's office
convinced government computers that the Town of Wallkill historian
actually lives in Wallkill.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security officials say they're not sure what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did get her back on the record as being alive and well,''
said Vivian Amato, a service representative at the Social Security
office in Newburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still don't know where I stand,'' Hunt-Ingrassia said.
''Every month I hold my breath and wonder what's going to happen
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallkill is in Ulster County, 66 miles north of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 1933 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
