<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court throws out $5 million punitive award  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal appeals court has overturned the $5
million in punitive damages awarded to a woman who was
strip-searched by jail guards.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in a ruling dated
Thursday let stand a $19,600 award for pain and suffering and
medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   A jury had announced both awards at a trial on a lawsuit brought
by Debra Ciraolo, 44, who had been arrested after a domestic
dispute in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She was ordered by two female guards to disrobe and then to bend
over and cough. The jury found the city had acted with wanton
disregard or indifference.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the jury verdict, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had
predicted the punitive damages portion of the verdict would be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides did not immediately return telephone calls
for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said it rejected the punitive award because
the city's unconstitutional policy had been adopted by municipal
officials without any clear endorsement of the policy by elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we emphatically deplore the city's conduct in adopting a
policy that this (federal court) had earlier clearly held
unconstitutional, the taxpayers themselves cannot be held to be
responsible for the policy,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed after lawyers said as many as 63,000 people -
and perhaps as many as twice that number - were illegally
strip-searched by guards in Manhattan and Queens in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Strip searches of people charged with misdemeanors and other
minor offenses are prohibited unless there is reasonable suspicion
that weapons or other contraband are being concealed.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the searches took place without the knowledge of
senior Corrections Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   The city said the strip searches occurred in error after a shift
in job functions between police officers and jail guards left
guards in control who did not realize it was illegal to
strip-search people who had not been arraigned.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Reilly, chief of the Department of Corrections, said
in court papers that the strip-searches were necessary because of
security concerns inside city jails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
