<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Delay Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda and Uganda did not withdraw as
planned Friday from the northern Congolese city of Kisangani, where
the erstwhile allies have fought in their mutual bid to oust
Congo's president.
</P>
<P>
   The two armies have clashed three times in Kisangani, the Congo
River port that both sides deem strategic for resupplying their
troops elsewhere in Congo. They were to have begun withdrawing
Friday but ''the final plan has not been agreed upon,'' said Lt.
Col. Hossein Akram, one of 30 unarmed U.N. military observers
stationed in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   He said discussions were continuing but refused to go into
details.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the U.N. Security Council demanded Friday that
Rwanda and Uganda withdraw their forces from Congo immediately and
threatened to consider possible sanctions if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimously adopted resolution, the council also said
Rwanda and Uganda should pay for the damage and deaths they
inflicted on the northern Congolese city of Kisangani, where they
fought pitched battles earlier this month, killing an estimated 300
people.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted at the close of a two-day meeting of
the warring sides in Congo's 2-year-old civil war that included the
foreign ministers of Rwanda, Uganda and Congo and representatives
of the key rebel groups and other foreign armies involved in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda sent their forces into Congo to back rebels
fighting to oust President Laurent Kabila. But differences over the
conduct of war and which of the three rebel factions to support has
led to fighting. The city is supposed to be handed over to unarmed
U.N. military observers.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had begun withdrawing when fighting broke out June 5.
The ferocious artillery battles ended seven days later when the
Rwandan army drove the Ugandans from the northern edge of the city,
making it possible for the observers deploy at the front line. At
least 150 civilians were killed and another 1,110 were injured in
the bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both armies have promised to withdraw unilaterally
to points at least 60 miles outside of the city and hand control
over to the U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan army spokesman Maj. Phineas Katirima said Ugandan forces
would be withdrawing from Kapalata training camp, seven miles north
of Kisangani, to Banalia, about 60 miles further north.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan troops were to pull out to the south and southeast of
Kisangani from the city's two airports as well as from the center
of town, Rwandan military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rwandans warned of a buildup of Ugandan troops in Buta,
161 miles north of Kisangani, where they said Ugandan planes had
been flying in troops and ammunition for the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Only humanitarian flights loaded with food and supplies were
landing at the main, Rwandan-controlled airport northeast of the
city after the Ugandans demanded that no planes from the Rwandan
capital, Kigali, or Goma, in extreme eastern Congo, be allowed to
land.
</P>
<P>
   Goma is the headquarters of the Rwandan-backed Congolese rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, commercial flights carrying fuel, sugar, maize, beer
and soft drinks land daily in Kisangani from Goma. The water route
from Kisangani to the capital, Kinshasa, has been closed since the
rebellion against Kabila broke out in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Under a peace accord signed last year between Kabila and the
rebels, a 5,537-strong U.N. force of observers and troops to
protect them is supposed to oversee the withdrawal of foreign
troops from Congo. Fighting on Kabila's side are troops from
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.N. Security Council continued Friday to
negotiate a resolution in New York with the warring factions in
Congo that would cement the withdrawal of foreign troops from
Kisangani. The French-sponsored draft calls for foreign armies to
withdraw from the country -- and threatens possible sanctions if
they don't.
</P>
<P>
   France, which is president of the Security Council this month,
hopes to adopt the resolution by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Rwanda, Zimbabwe and Namibia started to exchange
prisoners of war under the auspices of the International Red Cross,
Rwandan and Red Cross officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is part of the peace agreement and has been agreed
upon by the Joint Military Commission, on which sit representatives
of all the warring parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
