<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets from
the Los Alamos weapons lab have been located behind a copying machine within the
lab's secure area and are being evaluated, the Energy Department and government
sources said today. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said the two hard drives,
which disappeared six weeks ago, were ''found within the secure areas of X
Division which houses the vault'' where they had previously been kept. Other
federal officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the devices were
discovered behind a copying machine. One official said the general area had been
searched before, but he was uncertain that anyone had looked in the exact spot
where they were found.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lebanon Rejects Israeli Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In a setback for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Lebanon rejected the United Nations' verification of Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon, saying Israel still controls some Lebanese territory. Annan had
said earlier today at U.N. headquarters that the United Nations has confirmed
the Israeli withdrawal is complete. That announcement is supposed to clear the
way for U.N. troops to move into the border area and help Lebanese forces
restore peace and regain authority in the region.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mississippi Prison Escapees Caught
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOWELL, Ind. (AP) -- Two Mississippi prison escapees were captured today,
ending an intensive search for the men who allegedly hijacked several vehicles
and committed thefts in three states during their three weeks on the run.
Convicted killer John F. Woolard and convicted robber Roy Randall Harper
surrendered peacefully a few hours apart after being surrounded by police,
Sheriff John Buncich said. Indiana State Police captured Woolard, 37, this
morning in a field near the Indiana-Illinois line about 40 miles south of
Chicago. Harper, 42, was caught earlier walking along railroad tracks in the
town of St. John. Both men had loaded handguns tucked into their waistbands,
authorities said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Catholic Bishops Issue Web Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- America's Roman Catholic bishops issued a warning today
about sex and violence on the Internet and asked parishioners to sign pledges to
shun immoral media content. Internet use can be ''a little like visiting the
best theme park in the world and coming across a toxic waste dump,'' the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops said. The bishops, plan to ask Church
members to sign pledge cards annually for the next five years that commit them
to rejecting media that ''produce immoral content and demean the dignity of the
human person.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Spring 2000 Sets 'Hottest' Record
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to the National Climatic Data Center, Spring
2000 was the hottest on record for the United States. The agency said that
meteorological spring -- March through May -- averaged 55.5 degrees Fahrenheit
over the United States. That's 0.4 degrees warmer than the previous record, set
in 1910.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas A&AMP;M Suspends Bonfire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Texas A&AMP;M University is suspending its
traditional pre-game bonfire for at least two more years to give officials time
to improve procedures following an accident last year that killed 12 students.
''We will not have a bonfire this year,'' Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said
today. When it resumes, the bonfire will be far smaller and the construction
will be much more professionally run, he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bell Atlantic-GTE Deal OK'd
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators gave their blessing today to the merger
of Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp., a union that transforms one of the offspring of
the old Bell system into the nation's largest local phone company and wireless
provider. It allows the firms to launch a combined business under the new name
Verizon Communications.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 266; Nasdaq Gains 15
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply today after Xerox and a
regional banking company issued profit warnings. In its biggest selloff in two
months, the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 265.52 points to close at
10,449.30. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,584-1,307. The Nasdaq was up 14.82
at 3,860.56.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sampras Gains at Queen's Club
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Pete Sampras is in the semifinals at Queens Club, which he
feels is perfect preparation for Wimbledon. ''My game is where I want it to
be,'' Sampras said after defeating fellow American Bob Bryan 6-4, 6-4 today at
the grasscourt warmup tournament. The victory ran Sampras' grasscourt winning
streak to 22 consecutive matches. He has won the last two Wimbledons and Queens
last year.
</P>
