<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJames Montgomery Boice:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Rev. James Montgomery Boice, a Bible
teacher and a statesman for Reformation theology, died Thursday of
liver cancer. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Boice was pastor of Tenth Presbyterian Church since 1968. He was
the teacher on ''The Bible Study Hour'' radio program broadcast
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   He was chairman of the board of City Center Academy, a college
preparatory high school for inner-city youth founded 17 years ago
by Boice and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   A prolific author, Boice wrote or contributed to more than 60
books on the Bible and theology.
George C. Connor Jr.:
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- George C. ''Nick'' Connor Jr., a high school
coach who set up the basketball game that led to the unification of
Louisiana's black and white athletic organizations, died June 9 of
prostate cancer. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, a longtime coach, teacher and athletic director at St.
Augustine High School and former state representative, was the
Catholic school's first lay teacher and the first coach of its
track, basketball and football teams.
</P>
<P>
   Because of segregation, St. Augustine played only other
all-black schools during most of Connor's coaching career. In 1965,
however, his basketball team played and won a secret game against a
then all-white Jesuit High School. The game was played on a
Saturday morning in an otherwise empty gym.
</P>
<P>
   The game was considered a precursor to the unification of the
state's separate athletic organizations. In 1999, the story was
turned into a made-for-television movie, ''Passing Glory.''
Irving Lichtenstein:
</P>
<P>
   MARINA DEL REY, Calif. (AP) -- Dr. Irving Lichtenstein, who
revolutionized hernia surgery, died Sunday of Parkinson's disease.
He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenstein refined hernia operations, announcing his surgical
breakthrough at a 1964 American Medical Association convention.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, hernia surgery required full anesthesia and was
followed by six to eight weeks of bed rest. Lichtenstein insisted
that with his technique the surgery could be done under local
anesthetic and the patient could be released from the hospital the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   As a Jew who had personally faced discrimination during his
medical training, Lichtenstein had a passion for individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he helped put the ACLU of Southern California on sound
financial footing when he created what became the Roger Baldwin
Foundation, which continues to finance litigation and educational
activities.
Peter McWilliams:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Peter McWilliams, an outspoken proponent of
medical marijuana use who was awaiting sentencing on drug charges,
died Wednesday. cause of death was not released. He was 50.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams had cancer and was suffering from AIDS, according to
a statement from Libertarian Party supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams was to be sentenced in August for conspiring to grow
and sell marijuana to cannabis clubs. He pleaded guilty after a
federal judge forbade him to use California's state medical
marijuana law as a defense.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams was forced to stop using marijuana after he was
prosecuted, and his supporters contend his health deteriorated.
Lucy Phelps Patterson:
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Lucy Phelps Patterson, the first black woman
elected to the Dallas City Council, died Thursday after a battle
with pneumonia. She was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was elected in 1973 to the City Council and served
three terms. She also served as a social worker, a college
professor, a community advocate and to appointed government and
church positions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, running as a Republican, she lost a race for Congress.
Dora Tsatsos-Simeonidi:
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Dora Tsatsos-Simeonidi, a dancer and
choreographer who merged modern expression with ancient Greek
dramas, died Thursday from brain cancer. She was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Her work had a profound influence on Greek dance and helped
introduce contemporary styles in the Mediterranean country.
</P>
<P>
   Tsatsos-Simeonidi was the daughter of the late Greek President
Constantinos Tsatsos.
</P>
<P>
   She studied dance in Greece and later in New York under the
famous American dancer Martha Graham. From 1950 to 1958, she was
lead dancer in the avant-garde Greek troupe Chorodrama.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, she helped found the State Theater of Northern Greece
and choreographed its ancient dramas. She was choreographer of the
National Theater in Athens from 1975 to 1981, and served as its
director in 1992-93.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
