<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Mohawks Claim They Shouldn't Have To Pay Duties at Border
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Ontario and Quebec Mohawks, whose ancestors were
traders, say they have a right to bring goods into Canada over the
U.S. border without paying customs duties.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Mohawks from a reserve near Cornwall, Ontario, told
the Supreme Court of Canada on Friday that the right they seek
would not threaten Canada's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to the Supreme Court after Grand Chief Michael
Mitchell won his case at two lower courts that agreed the Akwesasne
Mohawk should have the right to continue trading traditions that
existed before Europeans arrived in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government challenged those rulings, arguing that
extending the right to Mohawks would threaten Canada's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The high court reserved its decision Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Anti-Poverty Activists Unapologetic Over Protest
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A day after anti-homelessness protesters hurled
bricks, paint bombs and Molotov cocktails at police in a violent
clash at the Ontario legislature, activists were unapologetic
Friday for one of the worst riots in the province's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not going to be denied,'' Gaetan Heroux, spokesman for
the Ontario Coalition Against Poverty, said of the protest
organized by his group.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a proud day yesterday, proud because we stood up,'' he
said as some of his fellow protesters appeared at a downtown
courthouse charged in the riot.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Mike Harris reiterated his disgust Friday with the
tactics of the protesters, some of whom showed up at the
demonstration prepared for a riot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was totally inappropriate,'' he said at the legislature.
''I don't think it has any place in a democratic free society, a
law-abiding society like Canada and Ontario.''
</P>
<P>
   The fierce hour-long clash erupted Thursday when a delegation
from the crowd of anti-poverty activists, union supporters and
homeless people demanded to address the legislature, a privilege
only sometimes granted to foreign heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of demonstrators and 29 police officers were injured in
the clash -- as well as eight police horses, including one that was
stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Newfoundland Premier Takes Aim at Ottawa in Shrimp War
</P>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) -- Premier Brian Tobin, once the
federal government's strongest provincial ally, has turned his back
on one of his Liberal brethren in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   The Newfoundland premier, a former federal fisheries minister
who leads Canada's only Liberal provincial government, said Friday
he supports calls for the resignation of Fisheries Minister Herb
Dhaliwal following a federal decision to grant a shrimp license to
Prince Edward Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no more confidence in the minister of fisheries and
oceans for Canada,'' Tobin was quoted as saying by Newfoundland
Fisheries Minister John Efford.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who is in Iceland to promote the province's Viking
festivities this summer, couldn't be immediately reached for
comment. But Efford relayed his conversation with the premier to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Dhaliwal's decision, handed down Thursday, has infuriated many
Newfoundlanders and damaged the reputations of the province's five
Liberal MPs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Calgary Man Accused in Brink's Robbery Found Guilty
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- A former military reservist was
convicted Friday in the botched, commando-style robbery of two
Brink's guards that ended in a hail of bullets at a Calgary
shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ryan, 32, was also found guilty of stealing more than
$100,000 from an automated teller machine.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the 1998 robbery, in which more than 80
gunshots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Disgraced former soldier Darnell Bass, who received a seven-year
sentence for conspiracy to commit the robbery, was the Crown's key
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Although police have been criticized in the two-year
investigation because only two of the eight people involved in the
crimes have been convicted, detective Tom Marriott said at least
they got the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever we got evidence and were able to lay a charge we did
that,'' said Marriott. ''Unfortunately on some people we weren't
able to collect enough evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan will be sentenced next week.
</P>
