<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Bishops Condemn Condom Use  </HEADLINE>
By HAROLD OLMOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian bishops have reaffirmed
the traditional Catholic Church position against the use of
condoms, countering a report that some church leaders were
considering allowing their use to check the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But the bishops' statement irritated government officials who
have been campaigning against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Eugene Rixen, bishop of Goias and a member of the
Brazilian Church's Health Pastoral, sparked a controversy this week
when he said some in the Catholic Church were ''reflecting'' about
allowing use of condoms to fight AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks, led top Brazilian church bishops to issue a
statement reasserting traditional church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Church has not changed its position on this point,'' the
statement issued on Thursday said. ''It is important to remind the
young people that the publicity of contraceptives as a kind of
efficient vaccine against AIDS is fallacious.'' They added that
condoms are only 60-65 percent effective in preventing AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The argument represents ''a disservice'' to the Brazilian
population,'' said Paulo Teixeira, coordinator of the Health
Ministry's anti-AIDS program.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bishops' statement had no scientific merit and that
''studies conducted by the World Health Organization prove that
condoms are 95 percent effective against transmission of HIV.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement came after a Vatican official, Monsignor Javier
Lozano Barragan, president of the Vatican's Council of Health,
addressed the meeting in a closed-door session.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has 200,000 registered cases of HIV, which causes AIDS,
and an estimated 400,000 unreported cases. Both figures are the
hemisphere's second highest after the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
