<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carjackers escape after robbery, 25-mile chase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLEASANTVILLE, N.J. (AP) - Two men stole $40 in a gunpoint
carjacking Friday before leading police on a high-speed chase that
ended when they jumped from the still-moving vehicle and escaped
into woods, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The men were caught Friday afternoon in Monroe Township,
Gloucester County.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when the two, driving a silver Toyota
Corolla, approached two couples who were standing next to a 1997
Jeep Cherokee on a street corner.
</P>
<P>
   After turning off the headlights of the Toyota, one of the men
fired a shot at the foursome and stole $40, some jewelry and a
pocketbook from two of them, police Detective Jose Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   One then stole the car and drove off, the other man following in
the Toyota, Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Police broadcast a description of the vehicles and Egg Harbor
Township police spotted it - with two people inside - near Cardiff
Circle, beginning the chase west on U.S. 322, which is known
locally as the Black Horse Pike.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling at more than 80 mph, the black Jeep was chased by Egg
Harbor Township police and State Police west into Monroe Township,
where it turned left onto White Hall Road, striking a sign as it
did so, according to Monroe Township Police Chief Edwin Berwick.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeep headed south on White Hall Road before veering off the
road and entering the White Hall School grounds, where the driver
lost control and the two occupants jumped out while the Jeep was
still moving, fleeing into nearby woods, Berwick said.
</P>
<P>
   The chase route was about 25 miles. Capt. John Pope of the Egg
Harbor Township Police Department said police could have driven
faster but didn't because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to drive reasonably and safely. This vehicle was not
doing that,'' Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a bigger issue, which is officer safety and other
vehicles. There are limits that we operate within, which they
didn't have. (Police) never lost them, they were never far
behind,'' Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the two who escaped were the same two involved in
the carjacking.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe Township authorities warned people in the White Hall Road
area to be on the lookout for the two.
</P>
<P>
   At about 2:30 p.m. Friday, Monroe Township police arrested one
of the suspects after he was seen at a pay phone in a bar parking
lot on the Black Horse Pike. Police said he was making arrangements
to be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   While police were on the scene, his ride arrived and he was
arrested because he had outstanding warrants, Monroe Township
police said. They did not release his name.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspect was arrested on White Hall Road.
</P>
<P>
   The carjacking suspects were identified as Kyle Wynder, 22, and
Antwan Freeman, 27, both of Vineland. Freeman used to live in
Pleasantville near where the carjacking occurred, Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder and Freeman were turned over to Pleasantville police and
were charged with armed carjacking, weapons offenses, making
terroristic threats, conspiracy and aggravated assault, Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   State Police also will file charges of eluding police and other
charges against the pair, Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder and Freeman were to be taken to the Atlantic County Jail
in Mays Landing. They were being held on $50,000 cash each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 2201 </TRAILER>
