<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Empress Dowager Dead at 97  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT STODDARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Empress Dowager Nagako, a witness to Japan's
century, from its drive to catch up with the West to defeat in
World War II and rebirth as one of the world's richest nations,
died Friday. The widow of Japan's Emperor Hirohito was 97.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako began having breathing difficulties early Thursday and
then fell into a coma, dying at home at Tokyo's royal palace, the
Imperial Household Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Much of her life as empress was spent in tumultuous times,''
Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori said. ''Even as society went through
big changes and faced difficult times, she always gave her best.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagako, a princess herself, was a modest wife who always showed
a subject's deference to her husband, but she and Emperor Hirohito
were willing to break tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessors on the Chrysanthemum Throne, the world's
oldest dynasty, Hirohito declined to take an heir-producing
mistress after Nagako gave birth to four girls but no boys. She
later bore two sons, including the present emperor, Akihito, as
well as another daughter.
</P>
<P>
   And in contrast to the rest of Japan's somber royals, Nagako
usually appeared in public with a big smile on her face, waving her
hand in the traditional gentle seesaw royal greeting.
</P>
<P>
   The matronly empress won the affection of the nation in a way
her scholarly, aloof husband never did.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her smiling warmth played an important role in spreading
affection for the imperial family after the war,'' the national
Asahi newspaper said in an editorial Saturday. ''As she grew older,
the public saw her as a gentle, chubby grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   But tradition is a hallmark of Tokyo's Imperial Palace, and
Japanese media widely reported that Nagako, along with other
members of the royal entourage, treated her daughter-in-law Michiko
harshly, in part because she was the first commoner to become
empress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, change crept into the moated royal enclave at the heart
of Tokyo, with the heir apparent to Emperor Akihito choosing a
career woman as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Masako did, however, give up her career to marry Crown
Prince Naruhito.
</P>
<P>
   Some see Nagako as a symbol of the palace's more traditional,
more exclusive days.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's the last person from the old system of the imperial
family, and I'm hoping that this will open the door to a new type
of imperial family,'' said Tokyo housewife Sumiko Omori, 66.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako married Hirohito in 1924 at age 20. They had seven
children. Their reign spanned Japan's military conquests in Asia,
defeat in World War II and climb from economic backwater to the
world's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   Hirohito assumed the throne in 1926 as a deity, a direct
descendant of the gods. He renounced his divinity in 1945, as
demanded by World War II's victors. He died on January 7, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A painter, poet and musician, Nagako specialized in the
traditional arts of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   She has been out of public view for years. Nagako last attended
an official event on April 29, 1987: Hirohito's 86th birthday
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako began to use a wheelchair in 1980 after damaging her
spine at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   Along with footage of Nagako's life, including her marriage to
Hirohito, an appearance at the 1964 Tokyo Olympic Games and a 1975
visit to the United States, TV news showed Emperor Akihito, Empress
Michiko, Crown Prince Naruhito and Crown Princess Masako arriving
to visit her on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After her death, the imperial family began the 150-day mourning
period, Kyodo News agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Flags throughout Japan were to fly at half-staff Saturday, a
spokesman for the prime minister's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Born March 6, 1903, Nagako was the eldest daughter and third
child of Imperial Prince Kuniyoshi Kuni. At 15, Princess Nagako was
one of several prospective brides selected for Crown Prince
Hirohito. They were married in an elaborate ceremony on Jan. 26,
1924.
</P>
<P>
   She became empress on Dec. 25, 1926, when Hirohito rose to the
throne on the death of his father, Emperor Taisho. Two years later
he was formally enthroned as the 124th emperor of Japan in rites in
the ancient capital of Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   They were married longer than any imperial couple in Japan's
history -- nearly 65 years.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements were not immediately announced. Officials
at the prime minister's office and the Imperial Household Agency
declined to comment on a Kyodo report that Nagako's funeral will be
held after next month's Group of Eight meeting on Japan's southern
island of Okinawa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 2203 </TRAILER>
