<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gymnast Miller To Compete  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMOND, Okla. (AP) -- Three months after announcing a comeback,
Olympic gold medalist Shannon Miller is competing this weekend for
the first time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is taking part in the Gymnastics Challenge 2000 in
Mississauga, Ontario, along with other top gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to get back into it,'' Miller said. ''I want to go
out and do the best I can and, hopefully, show that I'm ready for
the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the most-decorated American gymnast ever, led the U.S.
women's gymnastics team to the gold medal in the Olympics in
Atlanta four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the Challenge 2000, Miller faces gymnasts from China, France,
the Ukraine, Russia, Canada, Australia and South America, most of
whom are Olympic hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was the only American invited.
</P>
<P>
   ''These will be Olympic-level athletes,'' said her coach, Steve
Nunno. ''We chose to do it because they allowed her to do whatever
events she wants. We need flexibility in the first meet and they
gave it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said her return hasn't been easy, but she said she and
Nunno have been working to get her back in shape and ready for the
Olympic trials in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not in peak shape, but I don't want to be either,'' she
said. ''Steve has a plan. He wants me to peak at the right time so
I'll be able to perform at the big meets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 2218 </TRAILER>
