<DOCNO> APW20000616.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Last Look for Nicklaus  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Jack Nicklaus pulled his drive left,
bent over to pull the tee out of the ground and looked up in plenty
of time to catch a glimpse of his future.
</P>
<P>
   There, on the fieldstone porch of a multimillion-dollar home
alongside the 11th tee at Pebble Beach, two men in comfortable lawn
chairs stared back.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open is about to become a spectator sport for the man
who played it better than any other -- ever. Nicklaus said so
himself. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd say there's a pretty good chance this is the last,'' he
started, then stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very slim that I would play again. ... This place in many
ways started my golf game and almost 40 years later, maybe it's a
fitting place to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a minute or so later, when someone asked Nicklaus
about whether he'd ever consider coming back if the U.S. Golf
Association extended yet one more exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well,'' he began, ''if I won the Senior Open and I was playing
well and ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Stop right there, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's disappointing not making the cut, but it would be
hard to imagine a more fitting goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   On a sun-splashed afternoon, on the prettiest piece of ground
golf is played on, Nicklaus made a farewell tour and should leave
it at that.
</P>
<P>
   He had his oldest son, Jackie, toting his bag and his wife,
Barbara, standing behind the 18th green, red-eyed with tears, to
give him one last U.S. Open hug.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always said if he could play one last round, he wanted to
play Pebble Beach,'' she said. ''Obviously, he wanted to play four
rounds, but it was still wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus tried to say as much himself several times, but the
words wouldn't come out exactly that way.
</P>
<P>
   The hair is thinner and the middle thicker than when he was the
most fearsome presence in the game. But people who expect him to be
pleased with any effort have no idea what Jack is made of; even
now, concession speeches have to be wrung from him.
</P>
<P>
   At the Masters two years ago, the people in charge at Augusta
National honored 40 years of Nicklaus by putting his name on a
bronze plaque. An hour into Sunday's final round, he stubbornly put
it back on the leaderboard. Afterward, when his quest came up four
strokes short, the then-58-year-old Nicklaus took a seat in the
interview room.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would be pretty stupid to say I wasn't thrilled,'' he said
at the time. ''But I'd also be dishonest to say I wasn't
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday's final tour of Pebble Beach, Nicklaus was mortified
at moments, disgusted at others, humbled by a few, but finally
touched. He was applauded at every green and nearly every fairway,
but the truth is there were precious few shots worth clapping for
on his way to a round of 11-over par -- Nicklaus' worst Open score
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the cruelty golf inflicts, it also allows for a
graceful exit. And for once, with 44 Opens come and gone, Nicklaus
availed himself of that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was one of 75 golfers out on the course when fog
postponed completion of the first round. He played nine holes
Friday morning and when he arrived at the 18th tee a second time
late in the afternoon, he prowled the tee box and finally sat down
on a fence at the back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I took one big last look at it,'' he said. ''I was hoping
somebody would take a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Nicklaus turned to Jackie and said he was going for the
green in two at the 543-yard, par-5 hole. He hadn't even attempted
the feat in 20 years, yet there was nothing but memories left to
play for.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment props up a legend for only so long, but in this case
it was just long enough. Nicklaus drove his tee ball to the middle
of the fairway and airmailed a 3-wood to just in front of the
green. From there, accompanied by a growing roar, the ball rolled
to within 50 feet of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Nicklaus caught up with it, everybody in the
bleachers was standing and Nicklaus uncharacteristically milked the
moment for all it was worth. He pretended to be surprised to find
out he'd reached the green and he then stepped out of his putting
crouch when a seagull flying by squawked a goodbye of his own. Back
on the 18th fairway, meanwhile, old foe Tom Watson was applauding
and fighting back a few tears of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jackie told the old man to read the final putt himself.
Nicklaus missed.
</P>
<P>
   ''My eyes were blurry and I was trying to go through the
moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For just a heartbeat, you could sense how special this all was,
but Jack being Jack, he couldn't let it go.
</P>
<P>
   ''And,'' he finished, ''I topped the darned putt.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 2218 </TRAILER>
