<HEADLINE> Phillies 2, Braves 1  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling won for the first time in
over a month, striking out a season-high 11 Friday night to lead
the Philadelphia Phillies over Tom Glavine and the Atlanta Braves
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The ace of the Phillies' staff, Schilling had the team's highest
ERA coming in (6.34), which prompted him to throw extra batting
practice Monday, a day after his previous start.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling (2-4), backed by Mike Lieberthal's two-run homer,
allowed five hits in eight innings and walked two, reaching double
digits in strikeouts for the first time since last July 4. He
lowered his ERA to 5.62.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, he fanned Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga with
no outs and runners on first and third. After a walk to Brian
Jordan loaded the bases, he struck out Javier Lopez. Jeff Brantley
finished for his seventh save in seven chances.
</P>
<P>
   Since shutting out the Braves on 11 hits on May 7 -- his second
start following offseason shoulder surgery -- Schilling had been 0-4
with an 8.05 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   While he is 2-0 with a 1.64 ERA against the Braves, the
33-year-old right-hander is 0-4 with an 8.07 ERA in his other
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones gave Atlanta a 1-0 lead in the fourth with his
15th homer, but Lieberthal homered off the backdrop in left-center
following Mickey Morandini's leadoff single in the bottom half.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (7-3) allowed just four hits in eight innings, struck
out five and walked one.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling struck out six in the first five innings, his fastball
reaching 96 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine retired nine of 10 before Morandini's single in the
fourth. He allowed only one hit after Lieberthal's homer.
</P>
<P>
Notes@: Schilling has reached double digits in strikeouts 47 times.
... Seven of Atlanta's last nine batters struck out. ... Lieberthal
threw out Veras in the first inning and has nailed seven of the
last 10 runners attempting to steal. ... Jones extended his hitting
streak to 15 with the homer. ... The game marked the first time two
University of Pennsylvania alums faced each other in the majors.
Phillies center fielder Doug Glanville and Atlanta shortstop Mark
DeRosa both played baseball for the Quakers. DeRosa also played
quarterback for Penn. ... Desi Relaford committed two errors. He
leads the majors with 18 despite being the last starting shortstop
in the NL to make an error this season.
</P>
