<HEADLINE> Pacers Lead Lakers by 19 at Half  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jalen Rose scored 22 points and Reggie
Miller added 18 as the Indiana Pacers took a 64-45 lead over the
Los Angeles Lakers at halftime of Game 5 in the NBA Finals Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Eight 3-pointers, including four by Rose and three by Miller,
helped Indiana take leads of up to 20 points in the second quarter
as the Pacers made a strong bid to stay alive in the best-of-seven
series.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight baskets by Rose, including his fourth 3-pointer,
gave Indiana a 46-32 lead midway through the period.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Best, who bruised his shoulder in Game 4 and was
questionable until game time, scored two straight baskets in the
second quarter to push the Pacers' lead to 50-35. Rose then scored
two straight for a 54-35 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing minutes of the half, Miller scored a basket and
then hit two free throws after Kobe Bryant picked up his third
foul. The biggest lead for Indiana was at 64-44 before Shaquille
O'Neal hit one of two free throws with 10 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers shot 75 percent and hit all six of their 3-point
attempts in the first quarter, which ended with them ahead 39-28.
The Lakers' only lead was after Glen Rice hit one of two free
throws at the start of the game to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   A basket by Miller, a rebound basket by Rik Smits and the first
3-pointer by Miller gave the Pacers a 7-1 lead before the first Los
Angeles basket, a 3-pointer by Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which leads the series 3-1, tied the game at 9. But
two free throws by Smits and the first 3-pointer by Rose started
another big Indiana run.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Miller hit his second 3-pointer and was
fouled by Harper on the play. He hit the free throw to complete the
four-point play for a 22-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second 3-pointer by Rose made it 32-21, and his third
3-pointer in the closing seconds gave Indiana a 37-26 lead before
offsetting baskets by Robert Horry and Mark Jackson at the end.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 19 points for the Lakers, who shot 45 percent for the
half. No one else had more than seven points for the Lakers, and
Bryant had 6 points on 3-for-9 shooting.
</P>
