<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiapas Expelled Man Wins Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By ALEJANDRO RUIZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- A Denver man won a
court battle Friday against a Mexican immigration policy that
critics claim punishes foreign supporters of leftist rebels in the
southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Walter Arrellano threw out an order from Mexican
immigration officials to expel Kerry Appel from the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican immigration officials had ordered Appel to leave Mexico
after he attended a New Year's celebration in San Andres
Larrainzar, a town north of this city, sponsored by the Zapatista
National Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision of the authorities of the National Immigration
Institute was unfounded,'' Appel's lawyer Jose Montero said.
</P>
<P>
   Appel is one of hundreds of foreigner supporters of the region's
Zapatista rebels who have been ordered out of Mexico over the past
four years. But it was unclear if his decision would affect similar
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. citizen expelled earlier, Tom Hansen of the Mexico
Solidarity Network, also won a court victory last year, but the
government promptly re-wrote his expulsion order and expelled him
again. Hansen appealed those actions but lost an appeal to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The government denies targeting supporters of the Zapatistas,
who have attracted widespread international backing after leading
an uprising in 1994 to fight for democracy and demand greater
Indian rights. But most of those expelled have been members of
Zapatista support networks or human rights organizations abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Appel was summoned on Jan. 3 to immigration offices along with
several other foreigners suspected of violating their visas.
</P>
<P>
   The government accuses expelled foreigners of violating terms of
their visas by meddling in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Immigration Institute has 15 days to appeal the
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
