<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department and government sources said two
computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos weapons lab
have been found behind a copying machine within the lab's top-secret secure area
and are being evaluated. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said the two hard
drives, which disappeared more than six weeks ago, were found today in an area
that apparently had been searched before. Richardson said investigators are
looking into ''inconsistencies'' surrounding the whereabouts of the devices.
They have not ruled out the possibility that the two drives had been taken
elsewhere since last being seen in April.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas End Propaganda Broadcasts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Name-calling on the world's most heavily armed
border was replaced Friday with pop songs and words of reconciliation, as North
and South Korea stopped propaganda broadcasts across the Demilitarized Zone.
Relations between the two have warmed since this week's summit, when the Koreas'
leaders pledged to work together to end half a century of hostilities and unite
families separated by the Korean War. During the three-day summit, which ended
Thursday, North Korean leader Kim Jong Il ordered his state-controlled media and
military to stop all anti-South propaganda. South Korea reciprocated Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Verifies Israeli Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In a setback for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Lebanon on Friday rejected the United Nations' verification of Israel's
withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying Israel still controls some Lebanese
territory. Annan had said earlier Friday at U.N. headquarters that the United
Nations has confirmed the Israeli withdrawal is complete. That announcement is
supposed to clear the way for U.N. troops to move into the border area and help
Lebanese forces restore peace and regain authority in the region.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Catholic Bishops Issue Web Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- America's Roman Catholic bishops issued a warning today
about sex and violence on the Internet and asked parishioners to sign pledges to
shun immoral media content. Internet use can be ''a little like visiting the
best theme park in the world and coming across a toxic waste dump,'' the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops said. The bishops, plan to ask Church
members to sign pledge cards annually for the next five years that commit them
to rejecting media that ''produce immoral content and demean the dignity of the
human person.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Warmest Spring on Record for U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to the National Climatic Data Center, Spring
2000 was the hottest on record for the United States. The agency said that
meteorological spring -- March through May -- averaged 55.5 degrees Fahrenheit
over the United States. That's 0.4 degrees warmer than the previous record, set
in 1910.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AOL Customer Accounts Hacked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America Online confirmed today that some of their employee
accounts have been compromised by hackers, and that the accounts were used to
gain access to and view details of some personal user accounts. A spokesman for
AOL, the largest Internet service provider, said the company has ''employed
extra security measures'' to solve the problem. ''We are aware of these claims
that a small number of employee accounts have been compromised,'' said spokesman
Rich D'Amato, adding that the company was withholding further details of the
exploit until an investigation was completed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bell Atlantic-GTE Deal OK'd
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators gave their blessing today to the merger
of Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp., a union that transforms one of the offsprings of
the old Bell system into the nation's largest local phone company and wireless
provider. It allows the firms to launch a combined business under the new name
Verizon Communications.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 266; Nasdaq Gains 15
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply today after Xerox and a
regional banking company issued profit warnings. In its biggest selloff in two
months, the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 265.52 points to close at
10,449.30. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,584-1,307. The Nasdaq was up 14.82
at 3,860.56.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nicklaus Bids an Emotional Farewell
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Jack Nicklaus bid an emotional and unforgettable
farewell to the U.S. Open today, while Tiger Woods was just beginning. Nicklaus
signed for an 82, his worst score ever in 160 U.S. Open rounds dating to 1957,
but he left an appreciative gallery at Pebble Beach with one lasting memory --
at age 60, he reached the 545-yard 18th hole in two. Woods opened with a 6-under
65, the lowest U.S. Open round ever at Pebble Beach, before fog suspended the
first round yesterday. He kept that up today with an 18-footer for par on the
second hole, then rolled in a 20-footer on the next hole to reach 7-under.
</P>
