<HEADLINE> 500,000 Oil Barrels Go to Refinery  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in two days, the Energy
Department directed that 500,000 barrels of crude oil be taken from
the government emergency reserve and provided to a Gulf Coast
refinery that has been cut off from tanker deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The department said it would provide the oil to the Conoco Inc.,
refinery at West Lake, La., to replace crude oil that is prevented
from reaching the refinery because of a blockage in the Calcasieu
ship channel near Lake Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Conoco agrees to return to the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve an equivalent value of crude oil once the
shipping lanes are reopened. The first shipments of government oil
will be made to the Conoco refinery on Sunday, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department announced a similar arrangement on
Thursday with the Citgo refinery near Lake Charles. The government
reserve is not far from the two refineries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are taking this action to avert a possible shortfall in
gasoline and diesel fuel to American consumers at a time when
supplies for these fuels are already tight,'' said Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Conoco and Citgo refineries were cut off from normal
tanker deliveries this week when a commercial dry dock collapsed
into the shipping channel just north of the Intracoastal Waterway.
Only a small amount of oil is being withdrawn from tankers and
moved around the blockage by barge.
</P>
<P>
   The oil from the government reserve will keep the refineries
running at normal capacity until the blockage is removed,
department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The last oil exchange involving Strategic Petroleum Reserve,
which contains nearly 600 million barrels of oil, was in May 1996,
when 900,000 barrels was lent to Arco because of a blocked
pipeline. An exchange is different from a decision to sell oil from
the reserve, something the Clinton administration has declined to
do, saying the oil should only be used to address severe supply
disruptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 2303 </TRAILER>
