<HEADLINE> Red Sox 7, Blue Jays 4  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Carl Everett and Brian Daubach hit back-to-back
homers and Hipolito Pichardo rescued Pete Schourek from a shaky
start on Friday night as the Boston Red Sox beat the Toronto Blue
Jays 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi hit a two-run homer in the first inning to give
Toronto the lead, but Kelvim Escobar (5-8) gave back five runs in
the bottom half.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek he gave up two runs in the third to cut Boston's lead
to 5-4 and then loaded the bases with two out in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Pichardo (2-0) came on and struck out Tony Batista to end the
inning. The Red Sox reliever pitched 2 1-3 scoreless innings,
allowing two hits and an intentional walk while striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garces pitched two scoreless innings and Derek Lowe pitched
the ninth for his 16th save. Nomar Garciaparra drove in three runs
as the Red Sox moved into first place in the AL East, a half-game
ahead of the Yankees, who lost 3-1 to the White Sox .
</P>
<P>
   Escobar settled down after the first, shutting Boston out before
leaving with a 5-4 deficit with one out and one on in the seventh.
He was charged with six runs on nine hits and two walks, striking
out six.
</P>
<P>
   But it looked like he might never make it out of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman flied out to left for the first out, then Jeff
Frye singled and Trot Nixon doubled, both of them scoring on
Garciaparra's single off the Green Monster. Everett followed with
his 22nd homer, and Daubach hit his 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary walked and Wilton Veras singled, then Scott
Hatteberg flied out to right field. O'Leary tagged up, and he
appeared to score when Mondesi's throw eluded Batista at third and
Batista kicked it into the Toronto dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But Toronto appealed, and the umpires ruled O'Leary left second
too early. That erased the run and the error, and ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Pichardo had a rocky start with the Red Sox, failing to retire a
batter in his only other Fenway Park appearance on May 31, when he
was recalled from Triple-A Pawtucket. But in six outings since
then, he has trimmed his infinite ERA to 2.13, allowing just two
more runs in 12 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Mondesi's first-inning home run on Friday night helped
Toronto set a club record with homers in 15 consecutive games. It
was Mondesi's 13th of the year. ... Frye has hit safely in 10
consecutive games, and 22 of the last 23. ... Daubach had just nine
hits in his last 56 at-bats before homering in the first inning.
... The back-to-back homers by Carl Everett and Daubach were
Boston's fifth consecutive homers of the year. ... Offerman has
reached base safely in 17 consecutive games. ... Everett homered
for the sixth consecutive home game. ... The crowd of 33,638 was
the biggest at Fenway this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
