<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police continue manhunt for suspects in Central Park attacks  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Two young men on their lunch break studied the
newspapers Friday, scrutinizing photos of suspects police believe
participated in Sunday's attacks on girls and women in Central
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just looking to see if we know anyone,'' said Rudy Ruiz,
20, of the Bronx. ''If we do, we're turning them in for the reward
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Police believe up to 60 men were responsible for the harassment,
molestation and in some cases robbery of 47 women, ranging in age
from 14 to 40, including four tourists. On Friday, they released 17
more photos in hopes of adding to their arrest tally of 16. There
are videotapes of the 17 additional suspects committing crimes,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz and his friend were ready to help.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care if the person they're looking for is a good
friend - what they did was wrong and they should be punished,''
Ruiz said. ''And the money does not hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 men arrested so far, four have been found after people
called the NYPD's Crime Stoppers hotline. They were identified as:
John Taylor, 24, of Queens; Isaias Lozano, 20, of Queens; Manuel
Nunez, 18, of the Bronx; and Isaial Forbes, 18, of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   If these suspects are indicted, the police will pay tipsters
$2,000 each. If they're convicted, the city will kick in $10,000
for each.
</P>
<P>
   Nine suspects have surrendered. They were identified as: Steven
Burt, 32, of Jersey City, N.J.; Roberto Camacho, 16, of Inwood, on
Long Island; Julio de la Cruz, 22, of North Bergen, N.J.; Manuel
Vargas, 18, of the Bronx; Leslie Marcano, 19, of the Bronx; Mark
Daniels, 21, of Irvington, N.J.; Anthony Bryant, 25, of Manhattan;
Soto Jensen, 16, of Brooklyn; and Trevor Britton, 29, of Brooklyn.
All surrendered after seeing their photos either in newspapers or
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of the arrest of David Garcia, 33, of the
Bronx, were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Two suspects - David Rowe, 24, of Hempstead, on Long Island, and
Tremayne Bain, 23, of Brooklyn - were nabbed on Sunday after a
victim identified them.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir thanked the public for its
help, and asked people to continue to call the hotline at
800-577-TIPS.
</P>
<P>
   ''We even got a call from Italy this morning, from an Italian
tourist who was in the park that day who called to give us some
information,'' Safir said, adding that the tourist was a witness to
some of the attacks and was helpful. He declined to go into
specifics about the call.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 people caught, Safir said some have records, others do
not, and most did not know each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''This appears to be something that happened relatively
spontaneously, and apparently some of them did not really recognize
the seriousness of the matters they were involved in,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   While more than 75 detectives have been assigned full-time to
identifying and nabbing the suspects, Internal Affairs
investigators are focusing on whether any officers failed to help
victims.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 police officers and supervisors assigned to patrol the
area where the attacks occurred have been interviewed, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without prejudging, my sense is we'll probably find four or
five police officers who acted inappropriately while the vast
majority of them acted appropriately,'' he said. ''Those police
officers who acted inappropriately will be subject to discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said police have spoken to the seven victims who said they
were the ones to first notify police of the attacks. Five said the
police acted responsibly, and two said they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the arrested were arraigned Friday night on first-degree
sex abuse and riot charges. A sixth man was expected to be
arraigned later Friday night, and five others through the weekend.
The District Attorney's office would determine the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The five arraigned Friday were held on bails ranging from
$30,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe and Bain, who are friends, have been charged with
second-degree aggravated sexual abuse, first-degree sexual abuse
and second-degree robbery. Their case has been adjourned to Aug. 1,
and their attorneys continued to maintain their innocence. Both are
free after each posted $10,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, during his weekly radio address, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani urged residents and tourists to flock to the city's parks.
He again called the attacks a travesty, but said the majority of
officers did their jobs that day. Only one caller referred to the
attacks, asking the mayor to clarify some news reports, which he
termed ''somewhat exaggerated and mischaracterized.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended his show by saying: ''Make sure you get out into the
park, enjoy yourself, have a great weekend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-16-00 2313 </TRAILER>
