<HEADLINE> Horn of Africa Peace Is Fragile  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- As Ethiopia prepared to sign a
partial peace accord with its enemy Eritrea, doubts lingered in the
streets of its capital Friday that the ruinous conflict would end
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The two Horn of Africa foes are scheduled to sign an agreement
Sunday in Algeria ending hostilities in their 25-month border war.
Negotiations over delineating their bitterly disputed frontier are
to follow, an uncertain undertaking that could easily trigger
further fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia insists it will not withdraw its troops from Eritrean
territory until U.N. peacekeepers are deployed in a buffer zone
along the border. If clashes flare there again, Ethiopians already
know who to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simple because outside this country our neighbors know
the problem -- Eritrea is crazy,'' said Abebe Siyer, standing in the
souvenir shop where he works. ''He (Eritrean President Isaias
Afwerki) only wants to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Morning and night Ethiopians are inundated with reports over
state-run radio and television exulting ''valiant, heroic,
gallant'' Ethiopian soldiers and vilifying Eritrea's ''lying,
desperate, rogue'' regime.
</P>
<P>
   Both governments are renowned for waging war over the air waves
as well as on the battlefield. Asked Thursday when Ethiopia's
propaganda campaign would end, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi told diplomats he expected it to ''die a natural death over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan pledged U.N. support Friday
for the cease-fire and sent officials to Africa to discuss plans
for peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats have suggested a force of about 2,000 troops, but
others have said nearly double that many may be required.
</P>
<P>
   The war has not impinged heavily on daily life here, unlike in
Eritrea, a country of 3 million people where almost every household
has someone on the front lines and nearly 1 million people have
been displaced by the war.
</P>
<P>
   The front is 560 miles from the Ethiopian capital and the
economy has only recently begun showing war's ill-effects. In all,
both countries, two of the world's poorest, have spent more than $1
billion on arms since the war began in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the capital say food prices have increased and the
constant requests to contribute to the war effort have begun to
take their toll.
</P>
<P>
   The lucrative tourism industry is also lagging. Only 90,000
tourists visited Ethiopia last year, down from the 120,000 in 1997,
the year before the war began.
</P>
<P>
   The slacking economy has led to a growing clamor for the war to
end.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ethiopia needs only business, only development. We want peace
because war is unnecessary,'' Abebe said.
</P>
<P>
   In the ancient city of Axum, Ethiopia's main tourist attraction
45 miles from the contested border with Eritrea, teen-age boys
making their living hawking souvenirs say they have not seen
visitors for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to sell these for 40 birr ($5),'' said one boy, holding
up a miniature statue of the Queen of Sheba. ''Now all I see are
journalists, so I have to sell it for 20 birr.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as he and 60 million other Ethiopians are concerned, the
country's mission has been accomplished: the ''aggressor'' Eritrea
has been defeated, taught a lesson and put in its place. It's time
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's peace we can get business. We can do anything,''
said Bihanu Dendrr, a trader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-16-00 2314 </TRAILER>
