<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-16 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Lotto game's jackpot, sales are lagging  </HEADLINE>
sfnhr
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) - Connecticut's Classic Lotto game
hasn't had a grand prize winner for 47 straight drawings, the
second longest winner drought in its history.
</P>
<P>
   The last time there was a jackpot winner was Jan. 4, when Sandra
Welchans of Guilford and Norman Castner of Newington split the $3.7
million prize.
</P>
<P>
   Previously the Lotto game went without a winner for 51 drawings
between July 24, 1998, and Jan. 22, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer players and resulting smaller jackpots may be reasons for
the dry spell. Since Connecticut began participating in the
21-state Powerball lottery with its bigger jackpots, sales of its
own Lotto game have dropped off.
</P>
<P>
   ''As you have more products introduced into the market, things
change,'' Diane Patterson, marketing coordinator for the
Connecticut Lottery Corp. said Thursday. ''With the introduction of
Powerball, (some) people who played Classic Lotto went over to
Powerball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the state's Lotto game have dropped from $170 million
in November 1995 when Powerball was introduced in the state, to $51
million last year, when Powerball accounted for $124 million in
lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the slower Classic Lotto sales, the jackpot grows
more slowly than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Martineck, Online-Product Manager at the Connecticut
Lottery Corp., said the game takes between three and four weeks to
increase by $1 million. By contrast, for a six-draw run in 1988,
the game increased by $1 million the first draw, and then $2
million for each of the remaining draws.
</P>
<P>
   The jackpot in next Tuesday's drawing will be $14.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
