<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abe Hirschfeld convicted on criminal solicitation charge  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Abe Hirschfeld, the real estate developer and
frequent political candidate, was convicted Friday after his second
trial on charges of trying to hire a hitman to kill his business
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, 80, was found guilty of second-degree criminal
solicitation for offering to pay $150,000 to have Stanley Stahl,
his real estate mentor and partner of 40 years, killed in 1997
because of a business dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed contract killing never happened and Stahl, whose
76th birthday would have been Friday, died of natural causes in
August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Ira Beal allowed Hirschfeld, whose
first trial ended in a deadlocked jury, to remain free on $1
million bail.
</P>
<P>
   Recently released from Bellevue Hospital Center's jail ward
after doing 60 days for contempt of court, Hirschfeld faces up to
seven years in prison when Beal sentences him on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, a former New York Post owner who is running for the
U.S. Senate, did not comment as he left the Manhattan courthouse.
He still faces a second trial on tax evasion charges on July 31.
His first trial in the tax case also ended in a deadlocked jury.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Gilda Mariani said Hirschfeld's
murder scheme began when he gave Joseph Veltri, one of his building
contractors, $75,000 in fall 1996 as a down payment to a hit man.
</P>
<P>
   Veltri said he delivered an envelope containing the money to man
with a rough, raspy voice in the back seat of a chauffeured
limousine with tinted windows near Hirschfeld's office at 15 Penn
Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   After Hirschfeld gave him a second envelope to deliver, Veltri
testified, he looked inside and found photographs of Stahl and a
note with Stahl's name, address, telephone number and license plate
number. He called the police.
</P>
<P>
   One difference in the second trial was that Mariani had an
investigator show the jury that $75,000 in cash can be carried in a
large envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, 73, was told of the alleged plot and was not harmed, but
he did start riding in a bulletproof car and wearing a bulletproof
coat.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference in the second trial was that Mariani talked
about Stahl's security measures after he heard that Hirschfeld
wanted him dead.
</P>
<P>
   The jury got the case Thursday and deliberated about five hours
over two days before convicting Hirschfeld.
</P>
</TEXT>
